WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:13.100 --> 00:00:15.220
&gt;&gt; Grant Harris: Well, welcome
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:15.220 --> 00:00:16.810
Good afternoon.

00:00:16.810 --> 00:00:18.150
My name is Grant Harris.

00:00:18.150 --> 00:00:20.380
I am chief of the
European Division.

00:00:20.380 --> 00:00:24.190
And I thank you for joining
us today for this event,

00:00:24.190 --> 00:00:28.710
International Writing Program,
Celebrating Women's Voices.

00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:32.190
The Library of Congress'
Poetry and Literature Center

00:00:32.190 --> 00:00:35.800
and the European Division
cosponsor this event

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:39.340
in partnership with the
International Writing Program

00:00:39.340 --> 00:00:44.890
at the University of Iowa and
with the Bureau of Educational

00:00:44.890 --> 00:00:47.240
and Cultural Affairs,
which is part

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:50.090
of the U.S. Department of State.

00:00:50.090 --> 00:00:52.700
The European Division is
excited to be part of this.

00:00:52.700 --> 00:00:55.310
We enjoy having programs
with the Poetry

00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:58.420
and Literature Center, and it's
great to be able to collaborate

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:01.920
with the University of
Iowa's literature program

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:05.490
and the Department of State.

00:01:05.490 --> 00:01:07.810
The library has extensive
collections from

00:01:07.810 --> 00:01:10.320
and about every country
in the world,

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:12.210
and that is certainly
true for the countries

00:01:12.210 --> 00:01:16.040
of our three women writers
who will present today.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:19.370
Having these poets, short story
writers, and novelists here

00:01:19.370 --> 00:01:22.860
from Macedonia, Russia,
and Ukraine,

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:25.690
countries where Slavic
languages are used,

00:01:25.690 --> 00:01:28.300
helps bring our collections
alive.

00:01:28.300 --> 00:01:31.980
The library already has
numerous publications by two

00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:34.160
of the writers, and we
actually have a couple

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:37.220
of donations just
now from the third,

00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:38.860
so we're well represented.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:41.530
We've collected the
whole set now.

00:01:41.530 --> 00:01:44.640
So, please know that the
collections of the Library

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:47.710
of Congress are open to
everyone and we would like you

00:01:47.710 --> 00:01:49.980
to come back and use them.

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:53.620
I remind you now to
turn off your cellphones

00:01:53.620 --> 00:01:57.010
and recording devices for
the duration of the program.

00:01:57.010 --> 00:02:00.640
Also, please know that
this is being recorded

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:04.200
for a later Library
of Congress webcast.

00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:06.830
When we have the question
and answer session

00:02:06.830 --> 00:02:09.070
after the main presentations,

00:02:09.070 --> 00:02:12.630
understand that if you ask a
question you are consenting

00:02:12.630 --> 00:02:15.600
to be part of the webcast.

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:18.190
I now give the floor
to Mr. Robert Augburn,

00:02:18.190 --> 00:02:21.010
Director of the Office
of Citizen Exchanges

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:23.510
at the U.S. Department of State.

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:28.500
[ Applause ]

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:32.840
&gt;&gt; Robert Augburn: Well,
thank you very much, Grant,

00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:34.720
and good afternoon, everyone.

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:36.600
On behalf of the U.S.
State Department,

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:39.330
I would like to thank the
Library of Congress so much

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:41.620
for hosting us today,
and for all of you

00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:43.360
for coming out and attending.

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:46.320
It's especially exciting to
welcome the prestigious writers

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:50.160
from the IWP, the
International Writing Program,

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:52.490
who will share their work in a
place that, here in the Library

00:02:52.490 --> 00:02:55.450
of Congress, that is so
significant to our country.

00:02:55.450 --> 00:02:57.730
I'd like to congratulate
all the writers who are here

00:02:57.730 --> 00:02:59.850
on your selection
and participation

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:02.020
in this year's IWP
fall residency,

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:04.930
and we're very honored that
you could take the time

00:03:04.930 --> 00:03:06.800
to participate in it.

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:08.100
You know, we, at the
State Department,

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:11.290
as the representatives of
America abroad, we get it.

00:03:11.290 --> 00:03:13.600
We understand the
value of literature,

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:16.940
freedom of expression, and
creativity, and we believe

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:18.430
that this program helps

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:21.360
to support strong
civil society voices

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:23.410
in communities around the world.

00:03:23.410 --> 00:03:25.620
So, once again, I'm grateful
that you've taken time

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:28.070
to participate in the program
and really look forward

00:03:28.070 --> 00:03:30.750
to hearing about your
experiences here in the U.S.

00:03:30.750 --> 00:03:34.030
and some the influences
behind your work.

00:03:34.030 --> 00:03:35.970
As I've hoped you've
experienced during your time

00:03:35.970 --> 00:03:39.900
in the U.S. this autumn,
we're a country of many voices

00:03:39.900 --> 00:03:42.310
and many stories,
and we're delighted

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:44.280
that during your
time here in America

00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:47.310
that you've had the opportunity
to add your own stories

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:50.750
and experience firsthand
some of ours.

00:03:50.750 --> 00:03:53.840
We're also, at the State
Department, very honored

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:56.190
to be working with the
prestigious International

00:03:56.190 --> 00:03:58.810
Writing Program at the
University of Iowa.

00:03:58.810 --> 00:04:02.100
The IWP staff has
just done wonderful

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:04.160
in their continued
work on the program.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:07.340
And through our partnership
with the IWP we hope

00:04:07.340 --> 00:04:10.070
to enable writers
around the world

00:04:10.070 --> 00:04:11.980
to strengthen their voices.

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:14.840
You know, for more than 60
years the U.S. government has

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:18.090
supported exchange programs
that have brought citizens

00:04:18.090 --> 00:04:20.620
from around the world to the
U.S., and has sent millions

00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:24.190
of Americans abroad, and
writers are often the people

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:26.750
who shape the narratives
in their countries.

00:04:26.750 --> 00:04:29.550
So, your willingness to share
your own expertise is very

00:04:29.550 --> 00:04:31.390
much appreciated.

00:04:31.390 --> 00:04:33.580
It's my pleasure now to
hand over the microphone

00:04:33.580 --> 00:04:35.620
to Professor Christopher
Merrill.

00:04:35.620 --> 00:04:39.150
He's the Director of the IWP
at the University of Iowa.

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:42.120
He has conducted cultural
diplomacy missions to more

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:45.240
than 50 countries, and
readers around the world,

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:47.970
in more than 40 languages,
have enjoyed your poetry

00:04:47.970 --> 00:04:50.940
and your nonfiction and
you've done wonderful service

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:53.340
for the UN National
Commission for UNESCO,

00:04:53.340 --> 00:04:54.640
and you're an appointee

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:56.390
to the National Council
on the Humanities.

00:04:56.390 --> 00:04:58.510
So, thank you so much.

00:04:58.510 --> 00:05:04.150
[ Applause ]

00:05:04.150 --> 00:05:05.450
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
Thank you, Robert.

00:05:05.450 --> 00:05:06.750
Thank you, Grant.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:08.050
Welcome all.

00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:10.090
I also want to acknowledge
partners here

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:14.430
from the U.S. State Department,
Jay Rahman, Nina Murray,

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:17.350
Jill Staggs, our
longtime Program Officer.

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:19.480
My gratitude to Rob
Caspar [assumed spelling]

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:20.780
and Anya Creighton
[assumed spelling],

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:24.420
who make this place available
for the writers to come

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:27.400
at the very end of a
three-month long residency.

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:31.330
The writers, this year, we had
28 writers from 27 countries.

00:05:31.330 --> 00:05:34.640
We say to them on the first
day of the fall residency

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:37.280
that their main mission
is to write.

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:39.250
I hope that by the
end of the time

00:05:39.250 --> 00:05:42.640
in Iowa city they will have
written many new pages,

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:47.580
have made many new friends, and
gathered many new impressions

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:51.510
about life in America and
about the literary traditions

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:55.070
of the writers they
share this space with.

00:05:55.070 --> 00:05:57.240
We also give them a
bit of a busy schedule.

00:05:57.240 --> 00:05:59.340
We don't demand that
they do everything,

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:01.840
but we try to make it
as enticing as possible,

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:04.540
so time does run short, I think.

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:08.180
So, today the writers you see
here on the stage are going

00:06:08.180 --> 00:06:11.780
to give short readings and then
we'll open it up for discussion.

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:13.080
I'll have some questions,

00:06:13.080 --> 00:06:15.860
but I hope that this can
become a robust conversation

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:17.840
between all of us.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:20.490
Just a quick introduction
of the writers.

00:06:20.490 --> 00:06:22.440
You have fuller bios here.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:26.210
Alisa Ganieva, right here to
my left, is a fiction writer,

00:06:26.210 --> 00:06:30.630
critic, journalist,
from Dagestan in Russia.

00:06:30.630 --> 00:06:33.530
Among the books that she has
published in English are Bride

00:06:33.530 --> 00:06:36.250
and Groom and The
Mountain and The Wall.

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:39.810
Her very first book;
however, Salaam, Dalgat,

00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:43.930
which tells the story of the
life of a young Dagestani male,

00:06:43.930 --> 00:06:46.980
brought her to prominence
in an interesting way.

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:49.670
It was published under
a male pseudonym.

00:06:49.670 --> 00:06:52.580
It won the prestigious
debut prize out of something

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:56.350
like 65,000 entrants,
and there was a lag time

00:06:56.350 --> 00:06:57.980
between the announcement
of the winner

00:06:57.980 --> 00:07:02.320
and the ceremony giving her
the prize, during which a lot

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:05.550
of speculation abounded
in Moscow about,

00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:08.500
who is this young
Dagestani male writer?

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:12.450
So, you can imagine the
surprise when Alisa turned

00:07:12.450 --> 00:07:14.850
up to accept the prize.

00:07:14.850 --> 00:07:18.290
Next to her is Rumena
Buzarovska,

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:21.270
who is a Macedonian
fiction writer, editor,

00:07:21.270 --> 00:07:23.430
translator, and professor.

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:27.430
She has a Ph.D. from the United
States in American literature.

00:07:27.430 --> 00:07:30.210
I learned over the
course of the residency

00:07:30.210 --> 00:07:34.290
that in profound ways she
embodies that very conflict

00:07:34.290 --> 00:07:37.070
that we know about between
Macedonia and Greece

00:07:37.070 --> 00:07:41.160
over the name of this country,
because on her mother's side

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:43.470
of the family she is Greek.

00:07:43.470 --> 00:07:45.600
Her first book in English
translation will come

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:48.180
out next year called,
My Husband.

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:51.530
And sitting next to her
is Kateryna Babkina,

00:07:51.530 --> 00:07:53.150
fiction writer, poet,
playwright,

00:07:53.150 --> 00:07:56.210
filmmaker from Ukraine.

00:07:56.210 --> 00:07:59.640
She published her first
book at the age of 17,

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:02.780
and for American writers
that's enough to make you want

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:05.910
to slit your wrists to hear
stories like that [laughter].

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:10.170
And part of what we do in
the IWP in a UNESCO city

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:11.990
of literature, as Iowa city is,

00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:14.650
is we hope that we have
cross-fertilization

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:18.670
of international writers in
discourse with American writers,

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:21.140
and when they hear that somebody
like Kateryna published a book

00:08:21.140 --> 00:08:26.070
at 17, you can imagine the
collective sigh or chagrin.

00:08:26.070 --> 00:08:29.140
She's published three short
story collections, four volumes

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:32.790
of poetry, two novels, and
during the fall residency we got

00:08:32.790 --> 00:08:35.960
to see part of a film that
she made, the proceeds

00:08:35.960 --> 00:08:40.170
from which were dedicated to
raising money for the treatment

00:08:40.170 --> 00:08:43.490
of pancreatic cancer for
children in the Ukraine.

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:48.110
So, Alisa, Rumena,
Kateryna, the floor is yours.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.410
First Alisa.

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:56.870
&gt;&gt; Alisa Ganieva:
Hello, everyone.

00:08:56.870 --> 00:09:01.100
It's a tremendous honor for
me to be in this library,

00:09:01.100 --> 00:09:03.800
in this greatest
library in the world.

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:07.220
And thank you, Chris, for
your generous introduction.

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:10.070
I'll read two short
excerpts from my book,

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:12.160
which is called Bride and Groom.

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:14.980
And this, you may guess, from
the title, it's dedicated

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:19.190
to the matrimonial institution
in my native region of Caucasus,

00:09:19.190 --> 00:09:21.940
or Dagestan, which is
in the south of Russia,

00:09:21.940 --> 00:09:23.240
and which became a part

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:27.560
of Russia 150 years
ago, quite recently.

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:32.340
Iyeda [assumed spelling] strode

00:09:32.340 --> 00:09:36.410
over to us tapping her
heels hollowly on the floor

00:09:36.410 --> 00:09:40.890
and issued a command, don't
you dare try to keep it secret.

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:45.290
If you meet a guy in
Shala, tell him the truth.

00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:47.670
I'm not going to
meet anyone else,

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:49.980
Amishka [assumed spelling],
buried her face into the pillow

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:52.720
and burst out sobbing again.

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:56.600
What do you mean, won't meet
anyone, thundered Iyeda,

00:09:56.600 --> 00:10:00.040
though I'm sure she
didn't believe it herself.

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:02.200
First of all, you could
still get Kareem [assumed

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:03.500
spelling] back.

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:06.100
Threaten him, pin
him to the wall.

00:10:06.100 --> 00:10:09.320
No way, he'll tell everyone.

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:12.720
He's going to do that anyway,
I couldn't stop myself.

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:15.220
He's already proclaimed
it to the rooftops

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:17.190
that you've lost your owner.

00:10:17.190 --> 00:10:20.390
Iyeda jabbed me with her elbow,
sat down next to Amishka,

00:10:20.390 --> 00:10:22.940
and stroked her on the back.

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:25.620
Don't be upset, Amishka,
it won't help.

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:28.100
There are all kinds
of guys out there.

00:10:28.100 --> 00:10:30.070
There are even some
here in the settlement

00:10:30.070 --> 00:10:33.940
who could care less whether
you are virgin or not.

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:37.810
You're lying, Amishka,
blurted out amid her tears.

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:39.810
Lying? Take, Rusik
[assumed spelling] who lives

00:10:39.810 --> 00:10:43.340
across the tracks, the one
who takes tango lessons.

00:10:43.340 --> 00:10:47.180
Boo-hoo [phonetic],
Amishka just kept bawling.

00:10:47.180 --> 00:10:51.110
Look at her, boo-hoo, though
in this case you're right,

00:10:51.110 --> 00:10:53.620
they that Rusik doesn't
believe in Allah.

00:10:53.620 --> 00:10:56.480
But there are others, Mordan
[assumed spelling], cool guys,

00:10:56.480 --> 00:11:00.430
but the main thing is, don't
try to keep it a secret.

00:11:00.430 --> 00:11:03.400
Why, Amishka looked
up from the pillow?

00:11:03.400 --> 00:11:07.100
Well, first of all, Kareem
might go see your new fiance

00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:10.280
and blab everything,
or show at tape.

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:12.060
Did he take any videos?

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:16.170
I don't know, Amishka
burst into tears again.

00:11:16.170 --> 00:11:19.290
Well, let's say he
didn't take any pictures

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:24.040
and won't tell anyone, but
then doctors might let it slip.

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:26.110
What do you mean, doctors?

00:11:26.110 --> 00:11:27.410
Just listen.

00:11:27.410 --> 00:11:31.590
One of our relatives in the
city found a fiance for her son.

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:32.890
Everything's fine.

00:11:32.890 --> 00:11:34.290
Everyone is happy.

00:11:34.290 --> 00:11:36.890
And after the wedding, a
month goes by, and she runs

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:39.690
into a gynecologist
friend of hers.

00:11:39.690 --> 00:11:43.040
The friend congratulates her
and starts questioning her

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:46.710
about the girl, where they
found her, what her name is,

00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:50.780
and it turns out that this
fiance was one of her clients

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:53.670
and she had come in
for a hymenoplasty.

00:11:53.670 --> 00:11:57.250
So, this relative goes
ballistic, rushes home,

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:00.760
grabs her daughter-in-law
by the hair, and throws her

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:03.270
out the door, and
she was pregnant,

00:12:03.270 --> 00:12:05.880
though our relatives
refused to recognize the baby

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:08.800
because they didn't
know whose it was.

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:11.000
Did her parents take
her back, I asked?

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.840
Of course not.

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:15.290
She had to go to
Rostov or to Astrakhan

00:12:15.290 --> 00:12:17.890
to start a whole new life.

00:12:17.890 --> 00:12:20.590
Amishka lay forlorn and crushed.

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:22.570
She had been her
family's favorite.

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:24.320
It was hard to imagine
her [inaudible]

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:25.940
out of the comfortable life

00:12:25.940 --> 00:12:28.690
without friends or
anyone who cared.

00:12:28.690 --> 00:12:31.750
There are some girls, she
sat quietly and haltingly,

00:12:31.750 --> 00:12:34.590
stopping to swallow
the lump in his throat,

00:12:34.590 --> 00:12:36.700
like that prostitute,
Angela [assumed spelling].

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:39.010
They run around,
ride in guys cars

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:41.940
with practically nothing
on, spend all their time

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:44.940
in nightclubs, and then,
as though nothing happened,

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:49.230
they put on a veil and become
someone's second or third wife.

00:12:49.230 --> 00:12:51.010
Don't judge veiled women based

00:12:51.010 --> 00:12:53.910
on Angela's example,
Iyeda frowned.

00:12:53.910 --> 00:12:55.210
That's not the point.

00:12:55.210 --> 00:12:58.140
It's just that even the
worst of them can get lucky.

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:02.490
But, me, I fell in love,
made a mistake, trusted him.

00:13:02.490 --> 00:13:05.080
I also remembered Angela,
she was the daughter

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:06.760
of a divorced woman who worked

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:08.870
as a janitor in the
local prison.

00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:10.870
She was the talk of the town.

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:14.720
Rumor had it that [inaudible]
himself had seduced Angela back

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:16.390
in her youth.

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:18.820
After that she passed
from one man to another,

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:21.480
evidently feeling no
shame for her behavior.

00:13:21.480 --> 00:13:23.780
I had seen her cruising
down [inaudible] Avenue

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:27.640
in the backseat of a car full
of carousing young men howling

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:30.880
with laughter, or coming back
from the city on the main road

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:34.230
for some reason on foot in a
short skirt, smiling alluringly

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:38.410
at all the guys she passed
under a chorus of catcalls.

00:13:38.410 --> 00:13:42.420
What? Did Angela take the
veil, I couldn't help asking?

00:13:42.420 --> 00:13:44.440
She did, blabbered Amishka,

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:47.570
and some bigshot crook took
her as his second wife.

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:50.120
He comes out to visit
her sometimes.

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:51.430
Impossible.

00:13:51.430 --> 00:13:53.390
My thoughts were all jumbled up.

00:13:53.390 --> 00:13:55.760
Maybe you should
take the veil, too?

00:13:55.760 --> 00:13:57.630
[inaudible] I was angry.

00:13:57.630 --> 00:13:59.710
[Inaudible] what are
you talking about?

00:13:59.710 --> 00:14:04.370
If Amishka covers it's not
because that Angela did it.

00:14:04.370 --> 00:14:06.820
I heard a shrieking
sound and shuddered.

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:09.230
Amishka was laughing
hysterically, snorting

00:14:09.230 --> 00:14:11.870
and beating her hands
and feet on the bed.

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:13.450
She was trying to say something,

00:14:13.450 --> 00:14:15.500
but we couldn't understand
a word.

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:18.310
Iyeda ran out again
and brought some water.

00:14:18.310 --> 00:14:20.230
The poor girl calmed
down for a second,

00:14:20.230 --> 00:14:22.450
but then burst into tears again.

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:23.810
What are you blabbering about?

00:14:23.810 --> 00:14:28.010
Stop howling and tell
us, Iyeda chided her.

00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:30.940
Amishka buried her face
in the pillow again.

00:14:30.940 --> 00:14:34.130
It's just that I think I'll
have to be part of a hard-sell,

00:14:34.130 --> 00:14:39.460
forced on men as a bonus, or
like [inaudible], remember her.

00:14:39.460 --> 00:14:40.860
What, [inaudible]?

00:14:40.860 --> 00:14:42.750
What? You don't remember her?

00:14:42.750 --> 00:14:44.510
They lived at the station.

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:48.540
Her eldest sister was gorgeous,
but [inaudible] was cross-eyed,

00:14:48.540 --> 00:14:51.500
scrawny, and hideous to look at,

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:54.500
though basically a
nice person [laughter].

00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:58.830
And? And, so, these matchmakers
come from [inaudible].

00:14:58.830 --> 00:15:01.650
They are after the eldest
sister, the pretty one.

00:15:01.650 --> 00:15:04.640
But on the day of the wedding
the bride's mother switched her

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:07.290
out for [inaudible], because
no one would have taken

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:08.790
her otherwise.

00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:10.390
She was under the bridal veil

00:15:10.390 --> 00:15:13.260
and so they didn't
notice anything.

00:15:13.260 --> 00:15:14.560
So, then what?

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:16.520
Did they send her back?

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:17.890
No, they left her
in [inaudible].

00:15:17.890 --> 00:15:21.300
The mother-in-law
taunted her for five years

00:15:21.300 --> 00:15:23.030
until she gave her a grandson.

00:15:23.030 --> 00:15:25.630
She was a kind person and,
ultimately, they got used

00:15:25.630 --> 00:15:27.130
to her, came to love her,

00:15:27.130 --> 00:15:30.780
and now supposedly her husband
treats her like a queen.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:34.340
So, you see, I smiled, a
happy ending [laughter].

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:40.600
And there's another excerpt.

00:15:40.600 --> 00:15:42.250
After Marat's [assumed
spelling] mother got out

00:15:42.250 --> 00:15:44.230
and they pulled away
from the store,

00:15:44.230 --> 00:15:46.540
the two friends were
finally alone.

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:49.040
[Inaudible] burst out laughing.

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:50.340
What made you think, Marat,

00:15:50.340 --> 00:15:52.010
that my cousin would
be right for you?

00:15:52.010 --> 00:15:53.680
She's a real dragon.

00:15:53.680 --> 00:15:57.080
Don't you remember that
time she came out to see me?

00:15:57.080 --> 00:15:58.590
Marat did remember.

00:15:58.590 --> 00:16:00.340
Sabrina [assumed spelling]
had come just once.

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:02.180
They were about nine years old.

00:16:02.180 --> 00:16:04.740
The girls had a tea
party for their dolls

00:16:04.740 --> 00:16:07.230
in [inaudible] making
[inaudible] cutlets and soup

00:16:07.230 --> 00:16:09.930
out of water and
soggy bread crumbs.

00:16:09.930 --> 00:16:13.530
Little Sabrina spent the whole
time whining and complaining.

00:16:13.530 --> 00:16:15.120
Nothing satisfied her.

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:16.680
She needed to switch the dolls.

00:16:16.680 --> 00:16:20.060
She refused to be the guest and
insisted on being the hostess.

00:16:20.060 --> 00:16:22.900
Then the boys raided the party
like a plague of locusts,

00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:26.170
knocking the neatly groomed and
dressed dolls from their chairs,

00:16:26.170 --> 00:16:29.280
tipping the table over,
sending the refreshments flying,

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:32.570
and made off with the soup,
the only thing that was edible.

00:16:32.570 --> 00:16:35.680
Marat seemed to recall that
[inaudible] had been with them.

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:37.460
[Inaudible] assured
that he hadn't been.

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:39.680
You are mixing him up with
Abduliv [assumed spelling].

00:16:39.680 --> 00:16:41.610
Really? Maybe so.

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:43.620
How's Abduliv these days?

00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:45.920
He's got his engagement
party in a few days.

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:48.540
You're going to, Aunt Hadija
[assumed spelling] said so.

00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:49.930
Oh, yes, I remember.

00:16:49.930 --> 00:16:51.230
Yes, I am.

00:16:51.230 --> 00:16:52.910
He's so gullible.

00:16:52.910 --> 00:16:54.680
I could make him
believe anything,

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:58.460
all kinds of weird stories that
I had heard in court, though,

00:16:58.460 --> 00:17:00.190
who knows, maybe they were true.

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:01.980
Anything can happen.

00:17:01.980 --> 00:17:04.990
For example, filthy stuff,
you wouldn't like it.

00:17:04.990 --> 00:17:08.170
I expect nothing less from
you, Shah [assumed spelling].

00:17:08.170 --> 00:17:10.220
All right then, he's one.

00:17:10.220 --> 00:17:13.280
My colleagues told me
about a security guard

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:16.870
who raped a woman, a janitor,
in a village school, or rather,

00:17:16.870 --> 00:17:18.760
she said that he had raped her,

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:22.140
but the guard claimed
that she consented.

00:17:22.140 --> 00:17:24.540
That's the second time today
this topic has come up,

00:17:24.540 --> 00:17:25.880
Marat smirked.

00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:30.240
Anyway, this janitor stands by
her story, says she screamed

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:31.870
and tried to get away.

00:17:31.870 --> 00:17:33.730
They decide to check it out.

00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:35.600
The teachers would
have heard her

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:37.710
if she really had made a fuss.

00:17:37.710 --> 00:17:41.850
They conducted an
experiment, Shah chortled.

00:17:41.850 --> 00:17:43.410
What's so funny?

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:46.850
Picture this, they set up
everything the way it was

00:17:46.850 --> 00:17:51.240
on that day and had them
act the whole thing out,

00:17:51.240 --> 00:17:55.470
and the defendant up and
raped her again [laughter].

00:17:55.470 --> 00:17:58.050
What the -- I kid you not.

00:17:58.050 --> 00:18:00.660
They fired the prosecutor
for it.

00:18:00.660 --> 00:18:04.370
Are all your fables
below the belt?

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:05.770
[Inaudible] don't play naive.

00:18:05.770 --> 00:18:07.280
There was one more story.

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:09.350
This one supposedly
took place in the city

00:18:09.350 --> 00:18:12.430
in the police detective's
office, also rape.

00:18:12.430 --> 00:18:14.400
Shah, who does a better job

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:16.610
of entertaining you
than I do, Marat?

00:18:16.610 --> 00:18:19.480
So, anyway, this one
involves a carrot.

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:22.070
It was material evidence
and was on a shelf

00:18:22.070 --> 00:18:24.310
in the investigator's office.

00:18:24.310 --> 00:18:27.750
This coworker comes
in and he's hungry.

00:18:27.750 --> 00:18:31.000
Don't tell me he
eats the carrot?

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:32.300
Shah [inaudible] again.

00:18:32.300 --> 00:18:36.030
They drove past construction
sites, canopied [inaudible],

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:38.530
and highway petrol
posts barricaded

00:18:38.530 --> 00:18:40.570
on all sides with sandbags.

00:18:40.570 --> 00:18:43.400
Drowsy soldiers holding
automatic weapons peered

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:45.850
out from behind the sandbags.

00:18:45.850 --> 00:18:47.920
So, who is Abduliv
going to marry?

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:51.580
Marat leaned back in his
seat, a regular girl.

00:18:51.580 --> 00:18:55.120
I, myself, helped investigate,
check up on her past.

00:18:55.120 --> 00:18:56.910
Everything nice and clean.

00:18:56.910 --> 00:18:59.930
Though Abduliv has gotten
himself in some deep shit.

00:18:59.930 --> 00:19:03.420
There's a girl on the side and
she's about to have a baby.

00:19:03.420 --> 00:19:05.850
What? He's a jackass.

00:19:05.850 --> 00:19:09.120
When we were in graduate school
he kept wanting to copy me,

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:11.090
envying my success
with the ladies,

00:19:11.090 --> 00:19:13.530
and he would spend
his entire stipend

00:19:13.530 --> 00:19:15.640
on this one prostitute
once a month,

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:18.650
because that was the only
way he could get laid.

00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:21.910
Shah, again, [inaudible]
his strong, white teeth.

00:19:21.910 --> 00:19:23.820
I knew about that, Marat said.

00:19:23.820 --> 00:19:26.600
I used to get on
his case about it.

00:19:26.600 --> 00:19:29.890
Know what else he used to
do, Shah was on a roll?

00:19:29.890 --> 00:19:34.020
He'd buy some Viagra in the
drugstore, gulp it down,

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:36.690
then go to the [inaudible]
to the prostitute.

00:19:36.690 --> 00:19:39.750
The point was, he could plow
her several times in a row

00:19:39.750 --> 00:19:42.530
and save money that
way [laughter].

00:19:42.530 --> 00:19:45.920
Marat couldn't stop himself and
joined in friend's laughter.

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:48.570
Abduliv really was an idiot.

00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:50.220
What about the girl
who got pregnant?

00:19:50.220 --> 00:19:52.470
Did the -- did he buy her off?

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:55.250
It's the prostitute [inaudible]
and she's threatened to come

00:19:55.250 --> 00:19:56.620
to the matchmaking ceremony

00:19:56.620 --> 00:19:59.310
with her brothers
and ruin everything.

00:19:59.310 --> 00:20:01.620
Does the bride know about it?

00:20:01.620 --> 00:20:03.140
Not yet, but she will soon,

00:20:03.140 --> 00:20:07.030
Shah smacked his
lips and fell silent.

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:08.830
Thank you.

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:16.500
