00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:22.860
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: Hello.

00:20:22.860 --> 00:20:24.160
I'm very honored to be here.

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:27.150
Thank you for inviting me, and
also I'm very happy to be part

00:20:27.150 --> 00:20:30.410
of the International
Writing Program.

00:20:30.410 --> 00:20:35.200
On a matrimonial note, I
will also read a short story

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:38.840
that is the opening sort of
my book called My Husband,

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:43.070
which is 11 short stories
narrated from the perspective

00:20:43.070 --> 00:20:46.300
of the wife in the marriage.

00:20:46.300 --> 00:20:52.750
And this one was written
in bout of kind of anger,

00:20:52.750 --> 00:20:56.880
and it then propelled
the entire book.

00:20:56.880 --> 00:21:00.910
My husband, The Poet.

00:21:00.910 --> 00:21:04.550
I met Gohran [assumed
spelling] at a poetry festival.

00:21:04.550 --> 00:21:06.510
His hair was already
turning white.

00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:07.810
It's totally white now.

00:21:07.810 --> 00:21:09.350
And I think he hopes this adds

00:21:09.350 --> 00:21:13.010
to his new sex appeal,
as he once called it.

00:21:13.010 --> 00:21:16.000
He said it as a joke, but I
think he actually meant it.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.100
I wanted to ask if his
thinning hair and his scalp,

00:21:19.100 --> 00:21:21.940
with the color and sheen
of lumpy, hardened wax,

00:21:21.940 --> 00:21:25.000
were also part of his new sex
appeal, but I stopped myself.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.660
He's not good at
taking criticism.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:30.330
He gets mad quickly, and
when he's mad he starts

00:21:30.330 --> 00:21:31.630
with the insults.

00:21:31.630 --> 00:21:34.660
This lasts for days until
I do something self-abasing

00:21:34.660 --> 00:21:37.070
to stop him from being
unbearable, such as,

00:21:37.070 --> 00:21:40.610
accidentally reciting a
line from one of his poems.

00:21:40.610 --> 00:21:43.860
The other day he got really
mad at me when I refused

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:46.270
to read the poems he had
written the night before.

00:21:46.270 --> 00:21:47.710
I don't have time now.

00:21:47.710 --> 00:21:49.610
How about tomorrow, I told him?

00:21:49.610 --> 00:21:52.270
So, you don't have
time for three poems?

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:54.060
I felt the anger in his voice

00:21:54.060 --> 00:21:56.610
and right away felt
sorry I turned him down,

00:21:56.610 --> 00:21:58.930
but it was already too late.

00:21:58.930 --> 00:22:02.000
From now on, he'd take
anything I'd say the wrong way,

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:04.880
so I kept quiet.

00:22:04.880 --> 00:22:06.900
All right then, go and
nerd out all you want,

00:22:06.900 --> 00:22:08.690
he said, slamming the door.

00:22:08.690 --> 00:22:11.580
He tells me to nerd out whenever
I'm preparing to teach one

00:22:11.580 --> 00:22:13.880
of my classes, meaning

00:22:13.880 --> 00:22:15.710
if I really knew
history I wouldn't have

00:22:15.710 --> 00:22:17.610
to prepare for class.

00:22:17.610 --> 00:22:19.970
You either know it or you
don't, he once told me

00:22:19.970 --> 00:22:22.530
with a rude look on his face.

00:22:22.530 --> 00:22:24.910
When it comes to his poems
I really don't know --

00:22:24.910 --> 00:22:27.680
I really don't want to read
them, let alone listen to them.

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:30.600
He used to subject me
to that torture, too.

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:33.240
When we still loved each
other and before we had kids,

00:22:33.240 --> 00:22:36.280
we would make love and afterward
he would whisper poems in my ear

00:22:36.280 --> 00:22:39.090
as we lay there all
sweaty and out of breath.

00:22:39.090 --> 00:22:41.820
His poems were always
about flowers of some kind,

00:22:41.820 --> 00:22:45.650
about orchids, because they
reminded him of pussies,

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:48.900
about southern winds,
or about the sea,

00:22:48.900 --> 00:22:51.290
and there'd always be a
reference to some exotic spices

00:22:51.290 --> 00:22:54.260
and fabrics, like
cinnamon and velvet.

00:22:54.260 --> 00:22:58.500
Sorry. Something along the lines
of, my taste was like cinnamon,

00:22:58.500 --> 00:23:01.690
my skin was like velvet, for
example, or that my hair smelled

00:23:01.690 --> 00:23:03.700
like the sea, which
I know isn't true

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:06.550
since my mother told
me that my hair stank.

00:23:06.550 --> 00:23:07.970
Either way, in those moments,

00:23:07.970 --> 00:23:10.060
his words used to
really turn me on.

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:12.580
I'd get excited and want
to make love to him again,

00:23:12.580 --> 00:23:14.850
and even though he often
couldn't do it right away,

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:16.280
I would repeat his
images and words

00:23:16.280 --> 00:23:18.400
to myself and get turned on.

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:21.300
He doesn't do that
anymore, thank the Lord.

00:23:21.300 --> 00:23:24.030
I find his poetry so
repulsive that I don't want

00:23:24.030 --> 00:23:27.730
to read a single line of it, let
alone listen to him reciting it.

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:30.190
Sadly, that's something
I still have to do since,

00:23:30.190 --> 00:23:32.910
as I already said, Gohran
tends to get really mad

00:23:32.910 --> 00:23:36.000
and I don't want to expose
our kids to these fights,

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:37.940
or myself for that matter.

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:40.140
Ever since we stopped making
love as much as before,

00:23:40.140 --> 00:23:42.630
he's been reading his
poems aloud to me instead

00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:44.670
of letting me read
them on my own.

00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:46.860
I'd watch him standing in
the middle of the living room

00:23:46.860 --> 00:23:49.140
under the bright light
of the ceiling lamp,

00:23:49.140 --> 00:23:52.330
which emphasized bulbous
nose and ashy complexion,

00:23:52.330 --> 00:23:54.030
and it slowly started
to dawn on me

00:23:54.030 --> 00:23:57.150
that his poetry really
wasn't very good at all.

00:23:57.150 --> 00:24:00.050
Much of it isn't about
anything other than himself

00:24:00.050 --> 00:24:02.070
and how he writes poetry.

00:24:02.070 --> 00:24:05.700
I think it seriously
turns him on, literally.

00:24:05.700 --> 00:24:07.880
Here's an example.

00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:10.600
The scent she carries
is like autumn,

00:24:10.600 --> 00:24:13.150
dissolving like drops
of rain in her eyes.

00:24:13.150 --> 00:24:16.050
The words make this poem mine.

00:24:16.050 --> 00:24:18.870
Maybe this isn't
the best example,

00:24:18.870 --> 00:24:20.890
but it's if the only
one I know by heart.

00:24:20.890 --> 00:24:22.190
Chris, you're making me --

00:24:22.190 --> 00:24:24.020
I know why you're
laughing [laughter].

00:24:24.020 --> 00:24:25.820
I'm sorry.

00:24:25.820 --> 00:24:29.040
[ Laughter ]

00:24:29.040 --> 00:24:30.340
Because I sometimes happen

00:24:30.340 --> 00:24:31.960
to accidentally recite
the last three lines,

00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:35.990
the words [laughter] make
this poem mine, in an effort

00:24:35.990 --> 00:24:38.230
to get him to stop
being mad at me.

00:24:38.230 --> 00:24:41.620
I hum them rather, which
especially strokes his ego

00:24:41.620 --> 00:24:43.770
since he's always
wanted a musician

00:24:43.770 --> 00:24:45.840
to put his poetry to music.

00:24:45.840 --> 00:24:48.620
He doesn't realize this
would actually be impossible.

00:24:48.620 --> 00:24:51.890
His poems have no rhythm
and often no meaning either.

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:54.600
They're just strings of empty
words carelessly thrown together

00:24:54.600 --> 00:24:58.150
into verses so that the
uninitiated can spot some exotic

00:24:58.150 --> 00:24:59.870
word like cinnamon or velvet

00:24:59.870 --> 00:25:03.040
and think his poetry
really is all that.

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:05.180
That's what I used to think,
too, back when I was still young

00:25:05.180 --> 00:25:08.140
and stupid and fell
for such tricks.

00:25:08.140 --> 00:25:09.930
God, was I stupid.

00:25:09.930 --> 00:25:11.230
It really is incredible.

00:25:11.230 --> 00:25:13.400
I just can't forgive
myself for it.

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:15.500
Anyway, I was talking
about how we met.

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:18.110
As I already said, it
was at a poetry festival.

00:25:18.110 --> 00:25:19.670
I was working there
as a translator,

00:25:19.670 --> 00:25:21.150
which was something
I used to do as a way

00:25:21.150 --> 00:25:24.340
to make some money before
I started to teach history.

00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:27.140
One evening in the lobby of the
big hotel where all the poets

00:25:27.140 --> 00:25:30.570
and translators were staying,
we all gathered and sang songs.

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:33.540
I now realized that all
the poets were showing off.

00:25:33.540 --> 00:25:36.930
Not only did they write
poetry, these sensitive souls,

00:25:36.930 --> 00:25:39.040
but they also understood
traditional music.

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:41.630
They had a musical ear
and they could sing.

00:25:41.630 --> 00:25:44.190
That was when Gohran
appeared, too.

00:25:44.190 --> 00:25:45.720
Fitting with the
style of the evening,

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:47.580
he wore a white shirt
embroidered

00:25:47.580 --> 00:25:49.490
with a traditional
folklore pattern.

00:25:49.490 --> 00:25:52.510
I have to admit, he
really did look good in it.

00:25:52.510 --> 00:25:55.240
Gohran, after all,
was very handsome.

00:25:55.240 --> 00:25:56.540
Now that I think about it,

00:25:56.540 --> 00:25:58.650
that was the reason I
fell in love with him.

00:25:58.650 --> 00:26:01.380
His chest was like an
exquisitely shaped sculpture,

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:04.160
and his shoulders and arms
were so strong and hairy

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:06.530
that they made you wish
he'd never let you go,

00:26:06.530 --> 00:26:08.110
that he'd hold you
inside them forever

00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:10.280
and carry you off somewhere.

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:12.260
Anyway, Gohran didn't
sit with everyone else,

00:26:12.260 --> 00:26:14.440
but a little apart,
leaning against a wall

00:26:14.440 --> 00:26:17.680
with his head tilted to the
side, observing the group.

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:20.620
Suddenly seizing the moment
when everybody had quieted down,

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:23.190
he straightened up and
started singing a folk song.

00:26:23.190 --> 00:26:24.490
It surely must have been
[speaking foreign language].

00:26:24.490 --> 00:26:29.610
As I later found out, that's
the only one he knows.

00:26:29.610 --> 00:26:32.100
With his theatrical
hollering, his eyes closed,

00:26:32.100 --> 00:26:34.750
his head thrown back, and the
apple of his throat bobbing up

00:26:34.750 --> 00:26:37.520
and down, he looked
like a crowing rooster.

00:26:37.520 --> 00:26:38.820
I found him ridiculous,

00:26:38.820 --> 00:26:40.590
but at the same time couldn't
stop looking at his arms

00:26:40.590 --> 00:26:43.570
and his chest, imagining
him grabbing a hold of me.

00:26:43.570 --> 00:26:46.780
When he was done singing people
clapped and he looked my way.

00:26:46.780 --> 00:26:49.180
His eyes were a little
teary, probably as a result

00:26:49.180 --> 00:26:51.500
of the exertion from
all the crowing.

00:26:51.500 --> 00:26:54.120
Back then I thought they
were full of sorrow.

00:26:54.120 --> 00:26:56.210
I felt an urge to console him.

00:26:56.210 --> 00:26:58.180
That evening I consoled
him in his room,

00:26:58.180 --> 00:27:00.910
and that's how the
whole thing started.

00:27:00.910 --> 00:27:03.250
He's still going to poetry
festivals all the time.

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:05.230
He goes whenever his
work allows it, which,

00:27:05.230 --> 00:27:06.810
by the way, he's lousy at.

00:27:06.810 --> 00:27:10.340
I can only imagine what he does
that these poetry festivals.

00:27:10.340 --> 00:27:12.590
First of all, he brings
along half a suitcase

00:27:12.590 --> 00:27:14.430
of his thin little poetry books

00:27:14.430 --> 00:27:16.870
with their cheap
laminated covers.

00:27:16.870 --> 00:27:19.520
He's had most of them translated
into English and into several

00:27:19.520 --> 00:27:22.130
of the Balkan languages so that
foreigners can understand his

00:27:22.130 --> 00:27:24.140
meaningless blabbering.

00:27:24.140 --> 00:27:26.520
The language I speak doesn't
interest him, which is why,

00:27:26.520 --> 00:27:27.820
as if by some miracle,

00:27:27.820 --> 00:27:30.060
he's never asked me
to translate for him.

00:27:30.060 --> 00:27:32.220
And besides, he thinks
I'm no good at poetry,

00:27:32.220 --> 00:27:34.790
that I don't get it, since I've
been showing little interest

00:27:34.790 --> 00:27:36.730
in his endeavors lately.

00:27:36.730 --> 00:27:39.790
The translations of his
poems, though, are terrible,

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:41.130
not in terms of content.

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:43.880
His poems are already void
of any content, as they are,

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:46.550
but they're full of
grammatical mistakes, too.

00:27:46.550 --> 00:27:48.480
This is because of
his stinginess.

00:27:48.480 --> 00:27:50.250
He wants to have his
poems translated,

00:27:50.250 --> 00:27:52.130
but doesn't want to pay for it.

00:27:52.130 --> 00:27:54.640
So, he finds some poor girls
and, after seducing them

00:27:54.640 --> 00:27:57.880
with his mature sex appeal, he
gets them to translate his poems

00:27:57.880 --> 00:28:00.540
for free, or for
a miserable fee.

00:28:00.540 --> 00:28:02.630
I overheard him haggling
with them a few times,

00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:05.890
offering them copies of
his book as compensation.

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:10.270
I find this completely
embarrassing, but what can I do?

00:28:10.270 --> 00:28:11.570
Every time he comes back

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:13.950
from his poetry festivals he
shows me the pictures of his --

00:28:13.950 --> 00:28:15.850
on his digital camera.

00:28:15.850 --> 00:28:18.290
He usually gives the camera
to somebody else and asks them

00:28:18.290 --> 00:28:20.140
to take pictures of him.

00:28:20.140 --> 00:28:21.480
So, he has a lot of pictures

00:28:21.480 --> 00:28:23.420
of himself reciting
poetry while standing

00:28:23.420 --> 00:28:27.060
on a podium behind a
microphone and holding one

00:28:27.060 --> 00:28:30.300
of his ugly little
books in his hand.

00:28:30.300 --> 00:28:33.500
His poetic expression is
captured in all the pictures.

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:35.540
I tell him this openly
since, for some reason,

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:37.210
it seems to flatter him.

00:28:37.210 --> 00:28:39.740
His eyebrows are slightly
raised, but one's higher

00:28:39.740 --> 00:28:42.570
than the other, as if he
were simultaneously concerned

00:28:42.570 --> 00:28:43.980
and moved.

00:28:43.980 --> 00:28:45.820
His chest is sticking out.

00:28:45.820 --> 00:28:48.240
His hair is always freshly
washed, usually blowing

00:28:48.240 --> 00:28:49.540
in the springtime breeze

00:28:49.540 --> 00:28:52.000
of the coastal little town whose
festival he especially likes

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:53.720
the frequent.

00:28:53.720 --> 00:28:56.060
The other pictures often
show women, actually,

00:28:56.060 --> 00:28:58.060
they rarely ever show any men.

00:28:58.060 --> 00:28:59.570
I'm not worried about
the girls who work

00:28:59.570 --> 00:29:01.220
as volunteers at the festival.

00:29:01.220 --> 00:29:03.610
I don't think they'd be
into him since he's too old

00:29:03.610 --> 00:29:05.390
and ridiculous for them.

00:29:05.390 --> 00:29:07.060
I think he presents
more of a temptation

00:29:07.060 --> 00:29:10.110
to a different category
of women, those matrons,

00:29:10.110 --> 00:29:13.450
a little on the chubby side with
rolls of fat around their waists

00:29:13.450 --> 00:29:14.750
and underneath their armpits

00:29:14.750 --> 00:29:17.640
where their bras are
cutting into their flesh.

00:29:17.640 --> 00:29:20.120
They're dressed in
tight red or black tops.

00:29:20.120 --> 00:29:23.220
Their hair is usually black
and they wear red lipstick.

00:29:23.220 --> 00:29:27.320
Not infrequently, they have a
dramatic hat on their heads.

00:29:27.320 --> 00:29:30.570
Chunky, shiny jewelry adorns
their fingers and necks.

00:29:30.570 --> 00:29:33.180
Their goal is to emanate
mature femininity,

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:34.960
sprinkled with a bit of mystery.

00:29:34.960 --> 00:29:37.730
They want to smell like cinnamon
and have velvety soft voices.

00:29:37.730 --> 00:29:40.700
Let them. Maybe Gohran can help.

00:29:40.700 --> 00:29:42.630
I couldn't care less.

00:29:42.630 --> 00:29:45.520
At night, though, he'll snuggle
up to me and say, orchid,

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:47.890
open up, and I open up.

00:29:47.890 --> 00:29:49.190
Thank you.

00:29:49.190 --> 00:29:53.690
The translation of this is,
by the way, Ekaterina Petrova

00:29:53.690 --> 00:29:55.590
from the MFA program in
translation at the University

00:29:55.590 --> 00:29:58.570
of Iowa, and I'm really thankful
for her wonderful translation.

00:29:58.570 --> 00:30:00.370
Thank you.

00:30:00.370 --> 00:30:05.500
[ Applause ]

00:30:10.660 --> 00:30:13.060
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina:
Something is missing here.

00:30:13.060 --> 00:30:16.490
Hi. I'm very honored to be
here, as well as to be a part

00:30:16.490 --> 00:30:18.480
of International
Writing Program.

00:30:18.480 --> 00:30:20.340
Thank you very much for that.

00:30:20.340 --> 00:30:22.900
And, yeah, after listening
to [inaudible] piece,

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:26.310
I couldn't help recognizing
myself at some parts

00:30:26.310 --> 00:30:27.610
of description of her poem.

00:30:27.610 --> 00:30:32.800
However, I'm not going to recite
any poetry now, just in case.

00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:37.050
I'm going to read the essay
written during my stay at Iowa,

00:30:37.050 --> 00:30:39.590
at International Writing
Program, and translated

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:41.930
by Hannah Lalif [assumed
spelling], who was a student

00:30:41.930 --> 00:30:44.330
of International
Translation Workshop

00:30:44.330 --> 00:30:46.220
of the University of Iowa.

00:30:46.220 --> 00:30:48.960
So, everything comes
from Iowa here and now.

00:30:48.960 --> 00:30:50.890
So that one was Grandparent.

00:30:50.890 --> 00:30:56.780
Whenever you tell me about
it your eyes are shining

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:01.060
as if you reveal a great secret
to me, as if you open your heart

00:31:01.060 --> 00:31:04.150
and share the most intimate,
the happiest childhood memory

00:31:04.150 --> 00:31:07.680
with me, which might
be as well true.

00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:11.320
You tell me about it as if I
don't hear the same scene nearly

00:31:11.320 --> 00:31:14.390
every day from those
people, mostly old,

00:31:14.390 --> 00:31:18.090
because the young don't
recall their past that often.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:21.490
You're Ukrainian,
your face lights up.

00:31:21.490 --> 00:31:22.970
Oh, you now what?

00:31:22.970 --> 00:31:25.960
One of my grandparents
came from Ukraine.

00:31:25.960 --> 00:31:31.730
Wow, I say, for the past
100 times I just said, wow,

00:31:31.730 --> 00:31:36.300
and fell silent to open
up a space for the story,

00:31:36.300 --> 00:31:38.580
if there was one, of course.

00:31:38.580 --> 00:31:42.230
Over the past three months
that I lived in and traveled

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:46.160
around the United States, I
looked back to my homeland

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:49.980
and imagined it the way local
people told me about it,

00:31:49.980 --> 00:31:53.020
not the way I personally
knew it.

00:31:53.020 --> 00:31:57.720
I saw a boundless slant of
grandparents [laughter],

00:31:57.720 --> 00:32:02.420
gardens with swings,
endless sunflower fields,

00:32:02.420 --> 00:32:06.400
old bikes jingling along
the path, neat little house

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:11.230
and cozy apartments, smelling
of chicken broth and apple pie.

00:32:11.230 --> 00:32:16.150
In that country rivers and lakes
were there only for fishing,

00:32:16.150 --> 00:32:18.640
[inaudible] forests
to pick eat mushrooms,

00:32:18.640 --> 00:32:21.870
follow unusual animal
tracks, watch birds,

00:32:21.870 --> 00:32:24.270
and learn plants names.

00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:28.240
Flat fell there in the
winter so people could go --

00:32:28.240 --> 00:32:32.730
could go sledding and skiing,
while the ice was always nice

00:32:32.730 --> 00:32:35.820
and smooth, perfect for skating.

00:32:35.820 --> 00:32:38.210
There was only so
much people remembered

00:32:38.210 --> 00:32:40.030
about their grandparents.

00:32:40.030 --> 00:32:44.960
In that imaginary
country slow-paced,

00:32:44.960 --> 00:32:50.190
[inaudible] passing grandmas,
grandparent [inaudible].

00:32:50.190 --> 00:32:53.480
They read their grandparentish
[phonetic] newspapers and books,

00:32:53.480 --> 00:32:55.400
cook their grandparentish meals,

00:32:55.400 --> 00:32:59.210
watch their [inaudible]
grandparentish TV programs,

00:32:59.210 --> 00:33:02.320
listen to their grandparentish
morning radio shows,

00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:06.970
and came up with new [inaudible]
grandparentish stories.

00:33:06.970 --> 00:33:11.540
How did that imaginary land come
into being, you might wonder?

00:33:11.540 --> 00:33:14.650
Well, the very first
grandparent, or rather,

00:33:14.650 --> 00:33:19.550
great grandparent, arrived
to Jamestown in 1607

00:33:19.550 --> 00:33:20.980
in Captain John Smith's ship.

00:33:20.980 --> 00:33:25.940
It was only two centuries
later, in 1877,

00:33:25.940 --> 00:33:27.310
that the first significant
weight

00:33:27.310 --> 00:33:32.720
of grandparents' immigration
brought 350,000 grandparents

00:33:32.720 --> 00:33:36.440
to the States, where
most of them worked

00:33:36.440 --> 00:33:38.560
at [inaudible] coalmines.

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:41.240
It is a historical
fact that nearly 400

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:43.890
of those grandparents
[inaudible] as slaves

00:33:43.890 --> 00:33:48.330
at the [inaudible] plantations,
sharing those experience

00:33:48.330 --> 00:33:50.820
that most white Americans
were lucky to escape.

00:33:50.820 --> 00:33:54.620
And as of 20,000, the
second wave arrived

00:33:54.620 --> 00:33:57.450
between the two World Wars.

00:33:57.450 --> 00:34:02.250
During and after World War II
the United States got 100,000

00:34:02.250 --> 00:34:04.150
Ukrainian grandparents more.

00:34:04.150 --> 00:34:08.120
The first wave of grandparents,
still in there, yes,

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:10.000
[inaudible] on the American
shore in the final years

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:12.290
of the Soviet Union when
the government was too weak

00:34:12.290 --> 00:34:15.540
to support the Iron
Curtain, and immediately

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:16.840
after the USSR collapsed.

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:19.360
The fifth wave is
rolling right now.

00:34:19.360 --> 00:34:21.800
The fifth wave is
rolling right now,

00:34:21.800 --> 00:34:24.970
but it's members have not
become anyone grandparents yet,

00:34:24.970 --> 00:34:26.660
that's for sure.

00:34:26.660 --> 00:34:28.940
There are as many
Ukrainian grandparents

00:34:28.940 --> 00:34:32.640
in the United States as
people living in San Francisco

00:34:32.640 --> 00:34:34.740
or Austin, and slightly more

00:34:34.740 --> 00:34:38.050
than in Detroit,
Seattle, or Portland.

00:34:38.050 --> 00:34:41.840
What do those people tell their
grandkids when they reminisce

00:34:41.840 --> 00:34:45.520
about the days when they
lived back in the Ukraine?

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:47.740
What do old people remember best

00:34:47.740 --> 00:34:51.090
about their childhood
[inaudible], the time when,

00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:54.890
despite all the hardships,
they were strong, beautiful,

00:34:54.890 --> 00:34:57.780
full of hope, when their
hearts were burning,

00:34:57.780 --> 00:35:01.590
and their future is
promised unknown wonders,

00:35:01.590 --> 00:35:04.970
when they could rejoice that
all good scenes were still ahead

00:35:04.970 --> 00:35:06.270
of them.

00:35:06.270 --> 00:35:08.870
Those were the times
when they fell in love,

00:35:08.870 --> 00:35:12.690
did not lose their loved
ones yet, did not think much

00:35:12.690 --> 00:35:14.860
about the days passing by,

00:35:14.860 --> 00:35:18.710
the times when they could
change anything for the better.

00:35:18.710 --> 00:35:21.000
What memories did
they feel like keeping

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:23.090
when they became grandparents?

00:35:23.090 --> 00:35:24.730
Only the best ones.

00:35:24.730 --> 00:35:27.500
I'm sure I don't need
to tell you about it.

00:35:27.500 --> 00:35:29.620
Only the best ones, my dear.

00:35:29.620 --> 00:35:33.880
I never heard anyone tell
me so many wonderful scenes

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:38.310
about my home country as you
and the likes of you did,

00:35:38.310 --> 00:35:40.250
the things you learned
about my land

00:35:40.250 --> 00:35:43.150
from your grandparents' stories.

00:35:43.150 --> 00:35:46.560
During various events,
discussions, lectures,

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:50.910
and readings here in the U.S.,
I talk a lot about my country.

00:35:50.910 --> 00:35:55.030
I talk about the ongoing war
with Russia that claimed lives

00:35:55.030 --> 00:35:57.500
of more than 10,000 Ukrainians,

00:35:57.500 --> 00:35:59.740
about the bloody revolution
we went through a couple

00:35:59.740 --> 00:36:04.340
of years ago, about the Soviet
legacy we are trying to get rid

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:09.810
of day after day, about our
complicated past with wars

00:36:09.810 --> 00:36:13.510
and plunders, ethics and
tributes, slavery, or,

00:36:13.510 --> 00:36:15.830
as they call it, serfdom.

00:36:15.830 --> 00:36:19.390
The [inaudible] on our language
literature and [inaudible],

00:36:19.390 --> 00:36:24.850
the denial of rights for work,
religious freedom, and identity,

00:36:24.850 --> 00:36:28.610
famine and genocides,
pogroms and mass shootings,

00:36:28.610 --> 00:36:32.960
deportations, arrests, tortures,
and concentration camps,

00:36:32.960 --> 00:36:35.330
humiliation, misogyny,
and prejudice.

00:36:35.330 --> 00:36:41.050
I talk about all the scenes from
which the grandparents run away,

00:36:41.050 --> 00:36:43.820
all the things that
wouldn't let them survive

00:36:43.820 --> 00:36:48.150
and become actual grandparents
if they decided not to suffer,

00:36:48.150 --> 00:36:51.200
leaving everything
behind and flee.

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:54.850
All the scenes I still fight
against in my country today

00:36:54.850 --> 00:36:57.220
since that made us what we are,

00:36:57.220 --> 00:37:00.640
things that we are
working hard to change.

00:37:00.640 --> 00:37:04.600
But sometimes when I
meet people like you,

00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:08.970
people with grandparents
whose faces light up dreamily,

00:37:08.970 --> 00:37:12.400
their childhood memories
sparkling in their eyes,

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:17.550
it appears to me that I could
talk a little bit less about it,

00:37:17.550 --> 00:37:22.140
then that kind and blessed
grandparent's land would come

00:37:22.140 --> 00:37:25.310
to life, at least in those
American grandkids' imagination.

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:30.160
A Ukraine full of strength
and, yes, hopes and promises,

00:37:30.160 --> 00:37:32.960
a Ukraine where everything
is possible

00:37:32.960 --> 00:37:35.800
and all the good scenes
are still ahead of you.

00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:39.100
A Ukraine where everything
will be all right.

00:37:39.100 --> 00:37:40.900
Thank you.

00:37:40.900 --> 00:37:51.010
[ Applause ]

00:37:51.010 --> 00:37:53.000
