00:39:40.330 --> 00:39:44.300
So, yeah, or, you know,
they'll show off that, you know,

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:50.030
they can play some kind of
an instrument, you know.

00:39:50.030 --> 00:39:52.530
So, that's what made me
angry, because there's --

00:39:52.530 --> 00:39:56.620
you know, this is the thing,
yeah, Gohran is at the center

00:39:56.620 --> 00:39:59.980
of the short story, but he is
like so many Macedonian poets,

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:02.300
and also like so many
Balkan poets and, you know,

00:40:02.300 --> 00:40:03.600
poets around the world.

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:08.950
But back home it seems like
they really, really are excited

00:40:08.950 --> 00:40:12.030
by just writing about themselves
and feeling like Gods.

00:40:12.030 --> 00:40:13.960
You know, like men have God

00:40:13.960 --> 00:40:16.920
as someone they can
emanate, you know.

00:40:16.920 --> 00:40:19.230
And so, you know,
God then superheroes.

00:40:19.230 --> 00:40:21.500
And, so, they are
allowed to do this.

00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:23.030
Like they can write
about themselves,

00:40:23.030 --> 00:40:26.100
about how they create,
and then, you know,

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:29.290
sprinkle us with cinnamon or,
you know, something like that

00:40:29.290 --> 00:40:31.060
and then we will
feel great as women

00:40:31.060 --> 00:40:33.140
for being their inspiration
or something,

00:40:33.140 --> 00:40:35.200
so -- or, their audience.

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:38.850
So, I, you know, in ridiculing
that I, you know, don't feel bad

00:40:38.850 --> 00:40:42.990
that I wrote about a guy
because I ridiculed them, him.

00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:46.960
In the book I -- you know, I
don't -- I do write, you know,

00:40:46.960 --> 00:40:49.460
from a man's -- a man's
perspective sometimes as well,

00:40:49.460 --> 00:40:50.760
and it's not like I'm --

00:40:50.760 --> 00:40:54.600
but I will sometimes choose
particularly to tell the stories

00:40:54.600 --> 00:40:57.270
of women, or from a
woman's point of view.

00:40:57.270 --> 00:41:00.570
This particular, yeah, they're
all in the first person in all

00:41:00.570 --> 00:41:02.800
of the 11 stories, but they --

00:41:02.800 --> 00:41:06.590
you know, and the women in
them are also problematic.

00:41:06.590 --> 00:41:08.350
Like this one is
also problematic.

00:41:08.350 --> 00:41:09.650
They're not perfect.

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:10.950
And I also want -- I don't want

00:41:10.950 --> 00:41:13.390
to idealize women
-- is it working?

00:41:13.390 --> 00:41:14.690
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:41:14.690 --> 00:41:15.990
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: Yeah.

00:41:15.990 --> 00:41:17.290
I don't want to idealize
women also.

00:41:17.290 --> 00:41:19.390
I mean, I want to show that they
have -- you know, they're human,

00:41:19.390 --> 00:41:20.770
just -- and they
also have, you know,

00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:23.810
their bad sides and
their good sides.

00:41:23.810 --> 00:41:27.070
So, but, yeah, I feel like
there's not many women's voices

00:41:27.070 --> 00:41:30.390
in literature and
women's experiences,

00:41:30.390 --> 00:41:33.340
so I try to normalize that,
you know, by adding to it,

00:41:33.340 --> 00:41:36.980
because Macedonian
[inaudible] is male, too,

00:41:36.980 --> 00:41:39.730
but Macedonia especially.

00:41:39.730 --> 00:41:43.220
So, and I remember writing
this book and, you know,

00:41:43.220 --> 00:41:44.940
speaking to a guy
that I know in a cafe

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:46.240
and he said, oh,
you're a writer.

00:41:46.240 --> 00:41:47.540
So, what do you write about?

00:41:47.540 --> 00:41:48.840
I said, oh, you know,
I write stories.

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:50.140
What kind of stories?

00:41:50.140 --> 00:41:51.440
You know, stories about women.

00:41:51.440 --> 00:41:52.740
Would you read them?

00:41:52.740 --> 00:41:54.040
He said, nah, I wouldn't
read a story about a woman.

00:41:54.040 --> 00:41:56.810
So, this is -- this
is very common.

00:41:56.810 --> 00:41:58.770
And I think, you know, he just
said what other people are

00:41:58.770 --> 00:42:00.250
also thinking.

00:42:00.250 --> 00:42:03.170
So, yeah, this is
sort of my ideology.

00:42:03.170 --> 00:42:05.790
And this particular story was,
yeah, written out of the anger

00:42:05.790 --> 00:42:10.840
after reading like for the
gazillionth time a horrible poem

00:42:10.840 --> 00:42:12.780
somewhere in Macedonia
and someone, you know,

00:42:12.780 --> 00:42:15.680
like posting it on
Facebook or in some magazine

00:42:15.680 --> 00:42:17.610
and us having to fawn over it.

00:42:17.610 --> 00:42:20.370
So, and then I just -- all the
build up from all the years

00:42:20.370 --> 00:42:23.050
that I had been to this
festival, you know,

00:42:23.050 --> 00:42:26.150
exploded in this short
story, yeah [laughter].

00:42:26.150 --> 00:42:27.450
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill: Alisa,

00:42:27.450 --> 00:42:32.810
when you were reading I
was thinking to myself,

00:42:32.810 --> 00:42:34.550
first of all, you
do dialogue so well.

00:42:34.550 --> 00:42:39.020
But then I thought, how do
you get all these stories?

00:42:39.020 --> 00:42:41.900
I know you travel back
home from time to time,

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:45.170
but you must have your ears
alert in a -- in a special way.

00:42:45.170 --> 00:42:49.710
&gt;&gt; Alisa Ganieva: Yes, I
actually hear all the stories

00:42:49.710 --> 00:42:51.410
from different sources.

00:42:51.410 --> 00:42:56.660
And now I notice that
many of my acquaintances

00:42:56.660 --> 00:42:59.720
and relatives back home
shun me and stop talking

00:42:59.720 --> 00:43:02.110
when they see [laughter],
because they're afraid

00:43:02.110 --> 00:43:04.770
that they'll find themselves
in a book somewhere.

00:43:04.770 --> 00:43:06.570
&gt;&gt; They should be.

00:43:06.570 --> 00:43:09.120
&gt;&gt; Alisa Ganieva: But, also,
I'm trying not to write

00:43:09.120 --> 00:43:13.840
about real people, and all
of my characters are fiction.

00:43:13.840 --> 00:43:17.440
But, nevertheless, many of my
readers recognize their uncles

00:43:17.440 --> 00:43:20.680
and cousins and their
nephews in my novels,

00:43:20.680 --> 00:43:24.970
and they write me letters
asking where on Earth did I find

00:43:24.970 --> 00:43:27.870
out about their family story.

00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:30.120
So, the situations
are so typical,

00:43:30.120 --> 00:43:34.680
as in any realistic
piece of fiction,

00:43:34.680 --> 00:43:36.380
that it's very recognizable.

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:38.030
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
And the new --

00:43:38.030 --> 00:43:40.820
is that one of the reasons
why the new novel is set not

00:43:40.820 --> 00:43:42.700
in Dagestan, but
closer to Moscow?

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:45.660
Do you have to find
new material?

00:43:45.660 --> 00:43:46.960
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska:
It was the course

00:43:46.960 --> 00:43:49.330
of my natural internal
evolution.

00:43:49.330 --> 00:43:51.340
I had to step out of the frame.

00:43:51.340 --> 00:43:54.450
So, my fresh novel is
not about Caucasus.

00:43:54.450 --> 00:43:55.750
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill: Yeah,
can you say where [inaudible]?

00:43:55.750 --> 00:43:58.490
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: It's
called Offended Sensibilities,

00:43:58.490 --> 00:44:03.240
and the title, it repeats,
literally repeats the name

00:44:03.240 --> 00:44:07.150
of the fresh articles in
the Russian Criminal Code,

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:09.550
offending sensibilities
of the believers.

00:44:09.550 --> 00:44:14.590
It's one of the newly introduced
absurd laws that is used

00:44:14.590 --> 00:44:18.950
against dissenters and all
kinds of, mostly bloggers

00:44:18.950 --> 00:44:22.030
and journalists and people
who post things online,

00:44:22.030 --> 00:44:26.350
or who play Pokemon game
in a church, for example,

00:44:26.350 --> 00:44:29.010
or do some other things.

00:44:29.010 --> 00:44:32.520
And everybody heard
about [inaudible] case,

00:44:32.520 --> 00:44:36.190
which was also linked
to this situation.

00:44:36.190 --> 00:44:37.820
And the definition

00:44:37.820 --> 00:44:41.100
of the offending
sensibilities is very blurred,

00:44:41.100 --> 00:44:45.770
and nobody can definitely say
what it means, and this allows

00:44:45.770 --> 00:44:50.040
to apply it to anyone
who's not favorable

00:44:50.040 --> 00:44:51.470
for the government, for example.

00:44:51.470 --> 00:44:52.770
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
Would it --

00:44:52.770 --> 00:44:55.700
would you agree that part
of the writer's job is

00:44:55.700 --> 00:44:57.120
to offend sensibilities?

00:44:57.120 --> 00:44:58.420
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: Yeah,

00:44:58.420 --> 00:44:59.720
I'm always offending
someone's sensibilities,

00:44:59.720 --> 00:45:01.020
and sometimes I enjoy it.

00:45:01.020 --> 00:45:02.640
Maybe I'm [inaudible],
no, sadistic [laughter].

00:45:02.640 --> 00:45:04.940
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
Kateryna,

00:45:06.900 --> 00:45:10.390
I wonder if you could
talk just a little bit

00:45:10.390 --> 00:45:14.740
about going from forum to forum.

00:45:14.740 --> 00:45:17.310
You've written plays,
you've written poems,

00:45:17.310 --> 00:45:20.670
you've written films,
you've written novels.

00:45:20.670 --> 00:45:22.010
Here's a nonfiction piece.

00:45:22.010 --> 00:45:24.270
How do you -- how do you
figure out which forum

00:45:24.270 --> 00:45:26.820
to write what you write?

00:45:26.820 --> 00:45:28.250
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina: I've
been asked this question

00:45:28.250 --> 00:45:33.840
so many times, here in Iowa and
also before, and I never came

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:35.680
up with appropriate answer.

00:45:35.680 --> 00:45:37.680
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
That's why I'm asking.

00:45:37.680 --> 00:45:38.980
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina:
Because, yeah --

00:45:38.980 --> 00:45:41.970
well, and put in still in
the same situation again.

00:45:41.970 --> 00:45:44.160
Thank you, Chris.

00:45:44.160 --> 00:45:48.790
I would say it's all
the same thing for me.

00:45:48.790 --> 00:45:50.740
Like, transferring the --

00:45:50.740 --> 00:45:55.180
some certain kind of
emotional experience.

00:45:55.180 --> 00:46:02.920
And then, like, you know,
you need to make a chair and,

00:46:02.920 --> 00:46:05.290
depending on what
kind of chair you want

00:46:05.290 --> 00:46:09.100
to make, you pick the tools.

00:46:09.100 --> 00:46:12.510
Also, normally you can produce
a chair with any kind of tool,

00:46:12.510 --> 00:46:17.170
like using this one,
[inaudible] and,

00:46:17.170 --> 00:46:20.840
but then you would get different
kinds of chairs delivered.

00:46:20.840 --> 00:46:22.140
So, it's the same.

00:46:22.140 --> 00:46:23.440
Like I need to transfer
the story

00:46:23.440 --> 00:46:28.930
and the emotional experience of
the person being into the story.

00:46:28.930 --> 00:46:32.930
So, whether it's a play or the
novel or the poem or the book

00:46:32.930 --> 00:46:38.780
for children or the essay,
it only depends on the scale

00:46:38.780 --> 00:46:43.280
of the story and on
the size of and variety

00:46:43.280 --> 00:46:45.940
of experiences I
want to transfer.

00:46:45.940 --> 00:46:47.490
That's it.

00:46:47.490 --> 00:46:48.790
Did I explain it well?

00:46:48.790 --> 00:46:51.140
No, I didn't [laughter].

00:46:51.140 --> 00:46:52.440
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
I also want to follow

00:46:52.440 --> 00:46:55.710
up by having you talk just
a little bit about what --

00:46:55.710 --> 00:46:58.950
how the children's book came
about and how that turned

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:04.540
into a fundraising campaign for
children with pancreatic cancer.

00:47:04.540 --> 00:47:05.990
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina:
Pancreatic cancer.

00:47:05.990 --> 00:47:09.570
Somebody made a mistake
in there.

00:47:09.570 --> 00:47:11.380
I know nothing about
pancreatic cancer.

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:13.950
But, well, the first book

00:47:13.950 --> 00:47:15.950
for children I wrote
it occasionally.

00:47:15.950 --> 00:47:18.330
I wanted to write
a post on Facebook.

00:47:18.330 --> 00:47:19.680
It's a long story behind it.

00:47:19.680 --> 00:47:21.470
I didn't get a present
for [inaudible]

00:47:21.470 --> 00:47:25.410
and I was writing a post for
Facebook about growing up.

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:29.400
And at the [inaudible] I ended
up having the book for children.

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:33.940
It was no St. Nicholas Day or
present or myself mentioned.

00:47:33.940 --> 00:47:38.100
And then I was working with this
foundation, Ukrainian foundation

00:47:38.100 --> 00:47:41.490
for fundraising for
pancreatic cancer,

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:43.350
and it was the first
book for children.

00:47:43.350 --> 00:47:46.000
Because the book became
really popular and I wanted

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:49.730
to get something useful out
of the number of copies sold,

00:47:49.730 --> 00:47:52.080
so I made a deal with the
publisher that we're going

00:47:52.080 --> 00:47:56.050
to transfer some money from
each copy sold to the foundation

00:47:56.050 --> 00:47:59.070
that fundraises for
sick children.

00:47:59.070 --> 00:48:00.410
And it worked well.

00:48:00.410 --> 00:48:04.910
It worked like -- we raised
quite a serious amount of money.

00:48:04.910 --> 00:48:07.620
And then starting working
with his foundation I realized

00:48:07.620 --> 00:48:12.820
that we know so little about
what sick people really do

00:48:12.820 --> 00:48:17.070
and how their life
looks like in reality.

00:48:17.070 --> 00:48:22.930
Because this tragedy of having
a cancer blocks everything else,

00:48:22.930 --> 00:48:27.190
but in reality they are, besides
the cancer and the hospital

00:48:27.190 --> 00:48:30.500
and the medication, they
still have their daily life.

00:48:30.500 --> 00:48:33.830
Like they are playing,
they are having fun,

00:48:33.830 --> 00:48:35.280
they are having their
[inaudible],

00:48:35.280 --> 00:48:37.230
especially children.

00:48:37.230 --> 00:48:40.510
They are living,
even when they are

00:48:40.510 --> 00:48:45.620
like literally already dying,
for sure, they are still living.

00:48:45.620 --> 00:48:47.950
So, I really wanted
to talk about this.

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:51.250
To make people see those sick
people not only as a cancer,

00:48:51.250 --> 00:48:54.530
but also still as
people, as personalities.

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:55.980
So, that's the book
is what about.

00:48:55.980 --> 00:49:00.290
And, yes, and then we also turn
it into fundraising campaign

00:49:00.290 --> 00:49:01.590
and it was successful.

00:49:01.590 --> 00:49:03.510
It was 1 million
of Ukrainian money.

00:49:03.510 --> 00:49:08.200
I'm very bad in math,
but it's some thousands

00:49:08.200 --> 00:49:10.000
and thousands of
[inaudible] money.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:14.810
So, it was, I mean, the first
thing that was important

00:49:14.810 --> 00:49:19.620
to me is to tell about this
kind of problem in perspective

00:49:19.620 --> 00:49:24.440
of daily living with
[inaudible], because normally

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:27.380
when people -- and, also,
like when I was researching

00:49:27.380 --> 00:49:30.470
in hospitals, meeting doctors
and children, and actually not,

00:49:30.470 --> 00:49:33.960
not when I was researching,
when I was volunteering before,

00:49:33.960 --> 00:49:37.540
I saw kids being like really
frustrating when they get

00:49:37.540 --> 00:49:40.790
into the hospital, having
these serious health issues,

00:49:40.790 --> 00:49:43.740
and because they don't
know what is going on

00:49:43.740 --> 00:49:47.910
and they never had this kind of
experience, similar experience.

00:49:47.910 --> 00:49:50.410
They never saw it,
so they didn't --

00:49:50.410 --> 00:49:51.990
wasn't able to understand
what's going on.

00:49:51.990 --> 00:49:55.570
And then there was this book,
like it was a stupid book,

00:49:55.570 --> 00:49:58.060
totally, about the monkey.

00:49:58.060 --> 00:50:00.810
And the guy and the monkey,
so the monkey got sick

00:50:00.810 --> 00:50:02.990
and the monkey went
to the hospital.

00:50:02.990 --> 00:50:05.440
And monkey was taking
injections and everything.

00:50:05.440 --> 00:50:08.800
And then the monkey
got well and went back.

00:50:08.800 --> 00:50:12.050
And; however, the book wasn't
funny at all and nice at all,

00:50:12.050 --> 00:50:14.260
but they found this
book really supportive

00:50:14.260 --> 00:50:18.230
and children loved it, because
they saw that if this is

00:50:18.230 --> 00:50:22.560
in the book, monkey goes to the
hospital, I go to the hospital,

00:50:22.560 --> 00:50:24.530
then like nothing
awful is going on.

00:50:24.530 --> 00:50:26.520
So, they found it
really supportive.

00:50:26.520 --> 00:50:31.680
So, that was also the reason why
I wanted to have this book done.

00:50:31.680 --> 00:50:33.190
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
I should mention

00:50:33.190 --> 00:50:35.950
that Kateryna is quite
active on social media

00:50:35.950 --> 00:50:38.010
and has a lot of followers.

00:50:38.010 --> 00:50:42.510
So, you can see how she
documents her life there.

00:50:42.510 --> 00:50:44.080
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina: Yes,
and I love taking pictures.

00:50:44.080 --> 00:50:47.160
And then when I was
reading about poet

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:50.440
with digital camera
[laughter], taking his pictures,

00:50:50.440 --> 00:50:53.270
it was like [laughter].

00:50:54.550 --> 00:50:57.020
Just what all of us done here

00:50:57.020 --> 00:51:00.240
when you weren't here
for the sound check.

00:51:00.240 --> 00:51:02.560
First thing we done is
like taking pictures

00:51:02.560 --> 00:51:04.980
over there like us really --

00:51:04.980 --> 00:51:06.280
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska:
I participated

00:51:06.280 --> 00:51:07.580
in this, too [laughter].

00:51:07.580 --> 00:51:08.880
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
I should also note

00:51:08.880 --> 00:51:10.180
that at the closing party

00:51:10.180 --> 00:51:12.390
in Iowa city there was
a significant amount

00:51:12.390 --> 00:51:13.740
of karaoke, so.

00:51:13.740 --> 00:51:15.040
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: Yeah, so,

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:16.340
we know how to hold
a microphone.

00:51:16.340 --> 00:51:17.640
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:20.810
Are there questions
from the audience?

00:51:28.510 --> 00:52:29.040
[ Inaudible ]

00:52:29.040 --> 00:52:30.340
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: Well,
we've never heard a story

00:52:30.340 --> 00:52:31.810
from a man's side
before [laughter].

00:52:31.810 --> 00:52:34.470
We really want to hear it, too.

00:52:36.510 --> 00:53:34.170
[ Inaudible ]

00:53:34.170 --> 00:53:37.510
Well, they're not
my feelings, right?

00:53:37.510 --> 00:54:01.040
[ Inaudible ]

00:54:01.040 --> 00:54:02.340
That's the question?

00:54:02.340 --> 00:54:03.640
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:54:03.640 --> 00:54:04.940
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska:
Yeah, I don't know.

00:54:04.940 --> 00:54:07.930
You'd have to ask the character,
because I didn't write --

00:54:07.930 --> 00:54:10.050
I mean, I'm not the person
in the -- in the short story.

00:54:10.050 --> 00:54:12.560
And the short story only
gives you as much as it does,

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:14.650
and the rest of it is
your interpretation.

00:54:14.650 --> 00:54:21.400
So, I think my -- what
I -- what I said in it,

00:54:21.400 --> 00:54:22.770
you know, is pretty clear.

00:54:22.770 --> 00:54:27.980
And I'm glad that I also
raised this issue as you --

00:54:27.980 --> 00:54:30.610
I mean, what you did now is also
indicative of what I was trying

00:54:30.610 --> 00:54:32.470
to say, so, I -- yeah,
that's all I have

00:54:32.470 --> 00:54:34.120
to say about the story.

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:36.450
I hope you can read
it in English

00:54:36.450 --> 00:54:40.190
and read it again
when it comes out.

00:54:48.510 --> 00:55:24.540
[ Inaudible ]

00:55:24.540 --> 00:55:25.930
Thank you, thank you very much.

00:55:25.930 --> 00:55:27.260
My English is good
because I lived

00:55:27.260 --> 00:55:29.880
in the United States
several times.

00:55:29.880 --> 00:55:35.010
So, yeah, I didn't -- you know,
I didn't do this on my own.

00:55:35.010 --> 00:55:38.800
I was fortunate, in other words.

00:55:38.800 --> 00:55:41.200
The -- I don't write in English.

00:55:41.200 --> 00:55:43.090
I prefer to write in Macedonian.

00:55:43.090 --> 00:55:45.680
And I don't -- you know,
it's 2 million people,

00:55:45.680 --> 00:55:49.120
but it's also a very small
tradition and there's not

00:55:49.120 --> 00:55:51.190
that much literature
in Macedonia.

00:55:51.190 --> 00:55:54.050
I feel like I'm actually
doing something when I write

00:55:54.050 --> 00:55:57.400
in the language, that
I'm adding to it.

00:55:57.400 --> 00:56:00.150
And, regardless, even
poets like Gohran do it

00:56:00.150 --> 00:56:04.200
when they write their
crap, but -- in Macedonian.

00:56:04.200 --> 00:56:06.910
But I feel like this is
-- this is important.

00:56:06.910 --> 00:56:10.970
And I don't like to write in
English, but I do translate

00:56:10.970 --> 00:56:14.100
into English with help of other
writers, other translators,

00:56:14.100 --> 00:56:18.340
so maybe in the future I will
try to translate my own work.

00:56:18.340 --> 00:56:19.700
Thanks.

00:56:19.700 --> 00:56:21.760
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
I might just add to that,

00:56:21.760 --> 00:56:26.380
we encourage the writers to
write in their mother tongue.

00:56:26.380 --> 00:56:29.160
It is the case, from time to
time, that writers want to write

00:56:29.160 --> 00:56:31.920
in English, but at
the very beginning

00:56:31.920 --> 00:56:36.090
of the International Writing
Program we had the poet

00:56:36.090 --> 00:56:38.880
[inaudible], who always wrote
only in Slavonian, again,

00:56:38.880 --> 00:56:41.630
a language about the
size of the Macedonian,

00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:46.960
and because of translators,
and he had a lot of translators

00:56:46.960 --> 00:56:50.370
over the course of his life, he
became quite an influential poet

00:56:50.370 --> 00:56:52.820
in American literary circles.

00:56:52.820 --> 00:56:54.320
Because he was writing
in his mother tongue

00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:58.970
and then translators brought
the poem into English,

00:56:58.970 --> 00:57:02.890
that transmission is absolutely
essential to what we try to do

00:57:02.890 --> 00:57:05.650
in the International
Writing Program.

00:57:05.650 --> 00:57:08.240
I mean, I might ask
Alisa, you also have --

00:57:08.240 --> 00:57:10.820
you, in effect, you could have
chosen to write in Russian

00:57:10.820 --> 00:57:15.750
or in Avar, I think you made
decisions along this line,

00:57:15.750 --> 00:57:17.050
too, right?

00:57:17.050 --> 00:57:18.350
&gt;&gt; Alisa Ganieva: Yeah,
so, I have a mother tongue,

00:57:18.350 --> 00:57:23.390
which is called Avar, and it's
a very small ethnic minority,

00:57:23.390 --> 00:57:26.990
700,000 people, but not all
of them know the language.

00:57:26.990 --> 00:57:28.990
So, I spoke it until I was four.

00:57:28.990 --> 00:57:32.120
But then I was -- I started
attending a Russian-speaking

00:57:32.120 --> 00:57:34.610
kindergarten and I was
silent for two months

00:57:34.610 --> 00:57:36.740
because I didn't speak Russian.

00:57:36.740 --> 00:57:38.710
So, our supervisors thought

00:57:38.710 --> 00:57:42.230
that I was a very
dumb baby [laughter].

00:57:42.230 --> 00:57:46.800
And then the whole of my
education was in Russian.

00:57:46.800 --> 00:57:49.680
And I was raised in
Russian literary culture,

00:57:49.680 --> 00:57:53.830
so our language remained
my household language.

00:57:53.830 --> 00:57:58.440
So, I'm not sure that I'm
capable of writing something

00:57:58.440 --> 00:58:01.840
in literary of ours, because
mine is very dialectal,

00:58:01.840 --> 00:58:03.510
but it sounds peculiar
and it's fun

00:58:03.510 --> 00:58:07.130
to pronounce some
tongue-twisters sometimes.

00:58:07.130 --> 00:58:09.830
Like [speaking foreign
language], something like this.

00:58:09.830 --> 00:58:11.630
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:58:11.630 --> 00:58:15.180
[ Laughter ]

00:58:15.180 --> 00:58:16.790
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
Would you say

00:58:16.790 --> 00:58:19.460
that Avar shapes
your understanding

00:58:19.460 --> 00:58:20.780
of Russian as well?

00:58:20.780 --> 00:58:25.440
Are there any structural ways
in which the mother tongue

00:58:25.440 --> 00:58:28.900
on your literary tongue?

00:58:28.900 --> 00:58:31.900
&gt;&gt; Alisa Ganieva: Yeah,
any language is separate,

00:58:31.900 --> 00:58:38.290
is a different window, like a
poetic window, and point you

00:58:38.290 --> 00:58:40.360
to look at the reality.

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:45.200
And one of the fun things
I enjoy doing is comparing

00:58:45.200 --> 00:58:50.520
of proverbs or some
metaphorical expressions

00:58:50.520 --> 00:58:51.830
and different languages.

00:58:51.830 --> 00:58:56.930
Like when our people
get angry, annoyed by --

00:58:56.930 --> 00:59:01.340
annoyed by somebody, they say
you're jumping out of my eyes.

00:59:01.340 --> 00:59:05.740
So, these peculiar,
these bizarre expressions

00:59:05.740 --> 00:59:09.950
that look quite battered and
trivial in other languages,

00:59:09.950 --> 00:59:13.670
it's something that
we can learn from.

00:59:13.670 --> 00:59:14.970
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
Kateryna,

00:59:14.970 --> 00:59:16.270
do you want to [inaudible]
from the --

00:59:16.270 --> 00:59:17.570
you're living in
a country where --

00:59:17.570 --> 00:59:18.870
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina:
Russian, Ukrainian,

00:59:18.870 --> 00:59:20.170
I knew this was coming
[laughter].

00:59:20.170 --> 00:59:24.050
So, I have tell my --

00:59:24.050 --> 00:59:25.350
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
[Inaudible] predictable.

00:59:25.350 --> 00:59:26.650
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina:
My mother tongue,

00:59:26.650 --> 00:59:28.670
my first language is Russian,

00:59:28.670 --> 00:59:32.510
and that illustrates perfectly
the damage that was done

00:59:32.510 --> 00:59:35.050
to Ukrainian culture
and Ukrainian language

00:59:35.050 --> 00:59:37.420
by years of Soviet Union.

00:59:37.420 --> 00:59:42.170
Because both of my parents
and my grandparents were born

00:59:42.170 --> 00:59:45.550
at the territories of Ukraine

00:59:45.550 --> 00:59:49.880
and when they were children
they spoke Ukrainian and also

00:59:49.880 --> 00:59:54.500
like some my great-grandparents
came from Poland

00:59:54.500 --> 00:59:56.720
and other territories.

00:59:56.720 --> 00:59:59.040
Nobody ever was from Russia.

00:59:59.040 --> 01:00:02.880
But due to diversification,
like while diversification,

01:00:02.880 --> 01:00:08.120
when I was born all my
family was speaking Russian

01:00:08.120 --> 01:00:11.800
and considering themselves
Soviet people

01:00:11.800 --> 01:00:14.930
with all the Soviet
stuff in their head.

01:00:14.930 --> 01:00:20.270
So, the only persons peaking
Russian now is my mother.

01:00:20.270 --> 01:00:24.020
I do speak to some foreigners,
who like learned Russian

01:00:24.020 --> 01:00:27.400
and don't know Ukrainian,
so just the language

01:00:27.400 --> 01:00:30.490
of communication, I don't
mind Russian language.

01:00:30.490 --> 01:00:35.160
But the Russian policy and
nobody supports of Russian --

01:00:35.160 --> 01:00:41.320
like this invading parts
of Russian, I don't want

01:00:41.320 --> 01:00:43.670
to say Russian culture,
because Alisa is also part

01:00:43.670 --> 01:00:45.090
of Russian culture,
but, you know,

01:00:45.090 --> 01:00:48.590
like the normal one [laughter].

01:00:48.590 --> 01:00:52.080
No, I mean it.

01:00:52.080 --> 01:00:55.990
And though I write
only in Ukrainian

01:00:55.990 --> 01:00:58.970
and I speak in Ukrainian.

01:00:58.970 --> 01:01:03.810
Most of Ukrainians are bilingual
due to the Soviet past,

01:01:03.810 --> 01:01:06.120
but it's not because the
languages are so close.

01:01:06.120 --> 01:01:10.420
It's all because all the
education is at the start of it,

01:01:10.420 --> 01:01:12.900
and all the education
of my parents

01:01:12.900 --> 01:01:16.040
and people their age
was in Russian always.

01:01:16.040 --> 01:01:18.830
And you had to speak Russian
together like good positions

01:01:18.830 --> 01:01:22.300
for work and to be
teaching, and also writing

01:01:22.300 --> 01:01:25.110
in Ukrainian wasn't
easy, and you --

01:01:25.110 --> 01:01:26.610
it's not that you
won't be published,

01:01:26.610 --> 01:01:29.890
but you might have been
taken into concentration camp

01:01:29.890 --> 01:01:32.400
for writing certain [inaudible]
in Ukrainian, so it wasn't

01:01:32.400 --> 01:01:35.730
like really safe also.

01:01:35.730 --> 01:01:41.820
And, so, yeah, I mean, my
English is not good at all.

01:01:41.820 --> 01:01:44.020
I'm hardly able to read
this stuff translated

01:01:44.020 --> 01:01:46.770
by the good person with
the good English, so,

01:01:46.770 --> 01:01:49.780
I definitely never going
to write in English,

01:01:49.780 --> 01:01:52.850
but also I don't think I ever
going to do this in Russian,

01:01:52.850 --> 01:01:56.170
though my first language
is Russian.

01:01:56.170 --> 01:01:59.430
&gt;&gt; Alisa Ganieva: I'll just
add that this situation is --

01:01:59.430 --> 01:02:02.500
works for the whole
Soviet territory,

01:02:02.500 --> 01:02:05.500
because we have the same
linguistic disaster in Dagestan

01:02:05.500 --> 01:02:08.570
when grandparents speak
only their native languages

01:02:08.570 --> 01:02:10.300
and grandchildren
speak only Russian,

01:02:10.300 --> 01:02:12.000
so they can't communicate.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:14.960
And parents who are in
their 50's, they perform

01:02:14.960 --> 01:02:17.280
as translators between
different generations,

01:02:17.280 --> 01:02:18.610
and it's not normal.

01:02:18.610 --> 01:02:19.910
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill: Yeah.

01:02:19.910 --> 01:02:21.210
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: Can I
just add that this would be

01:02:21.210 --> 01:02:25.300
like me writing in Serbian or
Serbo-Croatian at the time.

01:02:25.300 --> 01:02:27.190
But Yugoslavia was
not, you know,

01:02:27.190 --> 01:02:31.070
it was the official language,
but it was not so insistent on,

01:02:31.070 --> 01:02:34.750
or, you know, authoritarian in a
way that, yeah, it was official,

01:02:34.750 --> 01:02:36.290
we learned it in
school, but it wasn't --

01:02:36.290 --> 01:02:37.860
it never was our first language.

01:02:37.860 --> 01:02:40.980
So, of course, nobody
who was Slavonian

01:02:40.980 --> 01:02:43.570
or Macedonian would write
or speak that language.

01:02:43.570 --> 01:02:45.920
So, just, you know, thinking
of it from the perspective

01:02:45.920 --> 01:02:49.060
that you were taking about
it, it's really tragic.

01:02:49.060 --> 01:02:50.540
And I want to go back to
what you said, you know,

01:02:50.540 --> 01:02:52.150
of the writing of
the first language.

01:02:52.150 --> 01:02:54.440
There is something, there's an
intrinsic connection, I believe,

01:02:54.440 --> 01:02:56.530
between the language that
you write in and the culture

01:02:56.530 --> 01:02:59.690
that you're presenting, and
I cannot do that in English.

01:02:59.690 --> 01:03:00.990
Like it just won't work.

01:03:00.990 --> 01:03:02.290
The idioms will not come out.

01:03:02.290 --> 01:03:04.300
And for me, it's
really important to have

01:03:04.300 --> 01:03:06.990
that in my own writing,
to feel that it is set

01:03:06.990 --> 01:03:08.290
in a particular place.

01:03:08.290 --> 01:03:10.620
That's what makes it different
from an American writer.

01:03:10.620 --> 01:03:12.990
And I'm not ever going
to try to be one.

01:03:12.990 --> 01:03:15.770
So, yeah, a good
translation is something

01:03:15.770 --> 01:03:19.530
that is able transfer it in
its own right, but never --

01:03:19.530 --> 01:03:22.740
but I would never go as --

01:03:22.740 --> 01:03:24.710
you know, I made that decision
a long time ago to never write

01:03:24.710 --> 01:03:26.010
in English because of that.

01:03:26.010 --> 01:03:30.170
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill:
Other questions?

01:03:30.170 --> 01:03:33.350
Yeah? This is Sandy
Barkin [assumed spelling],

01:03:33.350 --> 01:03:34.790
who one year was the director

01:03:34.790 --> 01:03:36.090
of the International
Writing Program.

01:03:36.090 --> 01:03:37.610
&gt;&gt; Oh.

01:03:37.610 --> 01:03:39.820
[ Inaudible ]

01:03:39.820 --> 01:03:42.700
&gt;&gt; I've really enjoyed
these readings.

01:03:42.700 --> 01:03:46.970
Kateryna, I -- this isn't really
a question, but just a comment,

01:03:46.970 --> 01:03:48.860
because I so loved your story.

01:03:48.860 --> 01:03:53.420
We are -- or, not
story, but your essay.

01:03:53.420 --> 01:03:56.680
We are so much a
country of grandparents.

01:03:56.680 --> 01:04:02.790
And I've never thought
in those terms before.

01:04:02.790 --> 01:04:08.510
And I hope that your
story [inaudible] I hope

01:04:08.510 --> 01:04:14.250
that your story wins its way up
to our central administration,

01:04:14.250 --> 01:04:16.720
because it's so important
to remind us

01:04:16.720 --> 01:04:21.090
that we are a country
with grandparents.

01:04:21.090 --> 01:04:22.390
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina:
Thank you very much.

01:04:22.390 --> 01:04:23.840
By the way, could I
use my chance to ask,

01:04:23.840 --> 01:04:25.140
is there some people

01:04:25.140 --> 01:04:26.440
in the audience [inaudible]
Ukrainian

01:04:26.440 --> 01:04:29.120
grandparents [laughter]?

01:04:29.120 --> 01:04:32.260
One, two, three, okay.

01:04:32.260 --> 01:04:34.170
Four, okay.

01:04:34.170 --> 01:04:38.250
So, that's the situation
normally.

01:04:38.250 --> 01:04:41.350
&gt;&gt; Christopher Merrill: I
should note that this book,

01:04:41.350 --> 01:04:42.650
this piece will appear

01:04:42.650 --> 01:04:45.070
in an online journal
called Off Assignment.

01:04:45.070 --> 01:04:48.420
I think you're working on the
edits right now with them, yeah.

01:04:48.420 --> 01:04:51.750
So, it's soon to
appear in English.

01:04:51.750 --> 01:04:53.550
I think --

01:04:53.550 --> 01:05:06.500
[ Inaudible ]

01:05:09.580 --> 01:05:15.100
&gt;&gt; Alisa Ganieva: It's too
easy to fall into this trap

01:05:15.100 --> 01:05:20.300
of self-pity, tragedy,
dark colors,

01:05:20.300 --> 01:05:24.600
and sometimes it's very
important to put the distance

01:05:24.600 --> 01:05:31.180
between the tragedy and
the readers, because many

01:05:31.180 --> 01:05:34.960
of my readers, for example,
they're used to wallowing

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:37.030
in their sorrows of
[inaudible] of Russia

01:05:37.030 --> 01:05:43.700
with all the Islamic
insurgencies and wrangles

01:05:43.700 --> 01:05:47.470
and political struggles
and corruption

01:05:47.470 --> 01:05:51.260
and police lawlessness, and
sometimes they want to relax

01:05:51.260 --> 01:05:55.620
or to find some new
perspective in literature,

01:05:55.620 --> 01:05:59.200
and humor makes it possible.

01:06:00.410 --> 01:06:02.080
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina: I would
also say it's much more

01:06:02.080 --> 01:06:06.050
challenging to make
people laugh then

01:06:06.050 --> 01:06:08.600
to make them cry
and feel unhappy.

01:06:08.600 --> 01:06:11.580
It's always easier to
transfer the experience of pain

01:06:11.580 --> 01:06:15.620
and tragedy and panic
or something like that.

01:06:15.620 --> 01:06:16.920
And, yeah, of course, when girls

01:06:16.920 --> 01:06:19.020
who are reading [inaudible]
really suffering

01:06:19.020 --> 01:06:21.650
because maybe it was
less funny [laughter].

01:06:21.650 --> 01:06:25.530
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: I
think also there's, you know,

01:06:25.530 --> 01:06:26.990
humor released tension.

01:06:26.990 --> 01:06:30.540
It kills sentimentality, which
is something that, you know,

01:06:30.540 --> 01:06:32.280
women are normally
associated with.

01:06:32.280 --> 01:06:33.590
So, screw that.

01:06:33.590 --> 01:06:37.470
And then there is -- yeah,
and it's entertaining.

01:06:37.470 --> 01:06:38.770
So, it's a winner.

01:06:38.770 --> 01:06:41.430
The other thing is that women
are not considered funny

01:06:41.430 --> 01:06:44.190
traditionally, and it goes
to show that that's crap.

01:06:44.190 --> 01:06:46.710
And, you know, it doesn't
-- also, it tells us that,

01:06:46.710 --> 01:06:49.660
you know, generally when
you have women associated

01:06:49.660 --> 01:06:55.720
with humor, actually humor is
out of the bounds for women,

01:06:55.720 --> 01:06:58.680
because it does everything
that, you know,

01:06:58.680 --> 01:07:01.960
traditionally women
are not supposed to do.

01:07:01.960 --> 01:07:03.830
So, lose control
over their bodies.

01:07:03.830 --> 01:07:06.450
You know, use their
intellect, and also be,

01:07:06.450 --> 01:07:11.850
you know, stimulating, so.

