01:09:17.020 --> 01:09:21.590
So, I'm that it will, at one
point, this whole experience

01:09:21.590 --> 01:09:22.890
of Iowa will be in there.

01:09:22.890 --> 01:09:25.790
I find it -- I've never
been to the Midwest.

01:09:25.790 --> 01:09:28.130
I haven't before.

01:09:28.130 --> 01:09:33.830
And, yeah, it was -- it was
very strangely hospitable,

01:09:33.830 --> 01:09:36.810
on the one hand, but also very,

01:09:36.810 --> 01:09:40.690
I wouldn't say there was a
lot of diversity in Iowa.

01:09:40.690 --> 01:09:47.160
But then this kind of
open heartedness I found.

01:09:47.160 --> 01:09:52.400
I'm still -- my impressions
are still settling.

01:09:52.400 --> 01:09:54.410
It was -- it was strange
to spend three months

01:09:54.410 --> 01:09:57.350
in a completely different
environment,

01:09:57.350 --> 01:10:00.640
which was somehow
contrasting in the --

01:10:00.640 --> 01:10:03.290
you know, that we
were on campus.

01:10:03.290 --> 01:10:07.700
And we were just saying,
Kateryna and Alisa yesterday,

01:10:07.700 --> 01:10:09.520
wow, it's so interesting
to see people

01:10:09.520 --> 01:10:12.310
who are not 17 [laughter],
you know what I mean?

01:10:12.310 --> 01:10:14.610
So, yeah.

01:10:16.280 --> 01:10:19.520
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina: Well, I
have this nice story of my state

01:10:19.520 --> 01:10:22.120
in Iowa, because
like it's really

01:10:22.120 --> 01:10:24.670
like a very contrasting
experience of [inaudible]

01:10:24.670 --> 01:10:29.380
and campus, like liberal
and wise and openminded.

01:10:29.380 --> 01:10:34.140
And then some other people from
Midwest who like in the taxis

01:10:34.140 --> 01:10:38.230
or meet somewhere in the
shops and in restaurants so,

01:10:38.230 --> 01:10:41.780
once I showed up for the
late breakfast at one

01:10:41.780 --> 01:10:45.980
of Iowa's restaurants, since we
didn't have kitchen in the hotel

01:10:45.980 --> 01:10:50.100
for three months, and
there was a waiting list

01:10:50.100 --> 01:10:54.510
for like 40 minutes, and then
there would be this couple,

01:10:54.510 --> 01:10:59.120
like [inaudible]
big people, farmers,

01:10:59.120 --> 01:11:01.820
but like wealthy
farmers, they invited me

01:11:01.820 --> 01:11:04.410
because they were first
in the waiting list

01:11:04.410 --> 01:11:07.500
and they got the big
table, so they saw I'm alone

01:11:07.500 --> 01:11:09.440
and they invited me to join.

01:11:09.440 --> 01:11:12.750
And I was like regretting
maybe should I or not,

01:11:12.750 --> 01:11:15.350
because it means also that you
not only like sit the corner

01:11:15.350 --> 01:11:17.720
and have you breakfast, you
have to share the conversation.

01:11:17.720 --> 01:11:20.390
And I wasn't sure it was nice.

01:11:20.390 --> 01:11:25.070
So, the first thing they sit
and speak, in my broken English,

01:11:25.070 --> 01:11:29.240
but really I wanted to eat, so I
accepted kindly the invitation.

01:11:29.240 --> 01:11:31.060
I decided if something
is wrong I'm going

01:11:31.060 --> 01:11:32.800
to pretend I don't
speak English at all,

01:11:32.800 --> 01:11:34.930
or speak English like hardly.

01:11:34.930 --> 01:11:37.690
And, so, they asked
me, where are you from?

01:11:37.690 --> 01:11:38.990
And I tell Ukraine.

01:11:38.990 --> 01:11:41.520
And yeah, I don't tell I have
the grandparent from there,

01:11:41.520 --> 01:11:44.000
but the first thing
they tell me, Ukraine,

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:46.080
oh my God, have you had poutine?

01:11:46.080 --> 01:11:50.690
And I'm like, whoop, and
then they told me, like,

01:11:50.690 --> 01:11:53.370
they were supporting this
since like [inaudible]

01:11:53.370 --> 01:11:56.730
and Black Lives Matter
and they [inaudible] live

01:11:56.730 --> 01:11:59.660
in the farm in Iowa city.

01:11:59.660 --> 01:12:02.550
They have 80 sheep or
something like that.

01:12:02.550 --> 01:12:04.180
We also saw their sheep later

01:12:04.180 --> 01:12:07.650
because they invited some
people to visit them.

01:12:07.650 --> 01:12:10.940
So, it's never what
you expect it to be.

01:12:10.940 --> 01:12:12.880
It's always surprising.

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:15.960
Sometimes it's like
surprising in a creepy way,

01:12:15.960 --> 01:12:17.920
but also sometimes
in a really nice way.

01:12:17.920 --> 01:12:21.150
And I definitely
wish I knew it more.

01:12:21.150 --> 01:12:25.710
So, probably I will come
again and discover it more.

01:12:30.510 --> 01:14:06.500
[ Inaudible ]

01:14:09.050 --> 01:14:10.350
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: So,

01:14:10.350 --> 01:14:11.650
I think we partially
answered this question.

01:14:11.650 --> 01:14:13.580
So, I write in the
language I know the best.

01:14:13.580 --> 01:14:20.620
And, but I have to say
that two of my novels,

01:14:20.620 --> 01:14:25.070
three of my novels, not two
of them, are set in Dagestan

01:14:25.070 --> 01:14:27.720
where people belong to
different ethnic minorities.

01:14:27.720 --> 01:14:30.570
They speak several
dozens of languages.

01:14:30.570 --> 01:14:36.280
And it's a big linguistic
audacity.

01:14:36.280 --> 01:14:37.580
It's a big phenomenon.

01:14:37.580 --> 01:14:40.870
And linguists come to
investigate these languages

01:14:40.870 --> 01:14:42.410
and to know more about them,

01:14:42.410 --> 01:14:44.880
although they are
disappearing nowadays.

01:14:44.880 --> 01:14:48.080
But, still, people
[inaudible] in Russian,

01:14:48.080 --> 01:14:50.890
because it's the only
common language they can use

01:14:50.890 --> 01:14:52.400
to understand each other.

01:14:52.400 --> 01:14:55.790
And, so, my dialects
and my colloquial parts

01:14:55.790 --> 01:14:58.580
in my novels are
written in this peculiar

01:14:58.580 --> 01:15:02.220
and broken Russian language
spoken by the local people

01:15:02.220 --> 01:15:06.560
who use their excerpts
from, and expressions

01:15:06.560 --> 01:15:10.960
from the local mother tongues,
from Arabic, from Turk language,

01:15:10.960 --> 01:15:12.780
from Persian language,
because there were

01:15:12.780 --> 01:15:15.610
so many influences
throughout the history.

01:15:15.610 --> 01:15:20.560
And, also, this is the
language spoken by men and boys

01:15:20.560 --> 01:15:22.330
on streets, and that was one

01:15:22.330 --> 01:15:25.370
of their reasons I wasn't
recognized as a female writer

01:15:25.370 --> 01:15:29.470
after I published
my first long story.

01:15:29.470 --> 01:15:31.920
So, when my personality
became obvious,

01:15:31.920 --> 01:15:35.880
some of the people started
rereading my writings

01:15:35.880 --> 01:15:38.210
to find the traces
of female pen,

01:15:38.210 --> 01:15:43.970
and they said how could you
hear and catch all this --

01:15:43.970 --> 01:15:46.540
all this men's talk,
especially in the slang,

01:15:46.540 --> 01:15:51.000
in this very peculiar slang?

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:53.150
So, I think we just
follow our heart.

01:15:53.150 --> 01:15:56.170
We're not conforming
with anything.

01:15:57.330 --> 01:15:58.960
&gt;&gt; Rumena Ruzarovska: I
don't think there's a rule,

01:15:58.960 --> 01:16:01.130
just like there is
no rule in terms

01:16:01.130 --> 01:16:03.600
of whether you can
translate into a language

01:16:03.600 --> 01:16:06.860
that is not native to you or,
you know, your mother language.

01:16:06.860 --> 01:16:09.150
Then there's the question of
-- because it's different.

01:16:09.150 --> 01:16:11.680
It depends on how comfortable
you are, how long you've lived

01:16:11.680 --> 01:16:14.600
in that particular culture.

01:16:14.600 --> 01:16:16.590
Then there's the, you
know, the mother language.

01:16:16.590 --> 01:16:18.340
What is the mother language?

01:16:18.340 --> 01:16:20.440
My mother's language was Greek.

01:16:20.440 --> 01:16:22.790
But she -- this is the
language that she speaks,

01:16:22.790 --> 01:16:25.650
but she doesn't -- that
she doesn't know that well,

01:16:25.650 --> 01:16:28.230
because she was raised
in [inaudible]

01:16:28.230 --> 01:16:30.480
where everybody spoke Russian,

01:16:30.480 --> 01:16:32.020
and this became her
mother language.

01:16:32.020 --> 01:16:33.920
Because, in fact, her mother
language was maybe the language

01:16:33.920 --> 01:16:36.380
of your school, of
your education.

01:16:36.380 --> 01:16:39.270
And then, you know, she was
Macedonian, so now she speaks --

01:16:39.270 --> 01:16:40.570
you know, she was very young,

01:16:40.570 --> 01:16:43.030
so then this also
became her language.

01:16:43.030 --> 01:16:46.880
So, you know, I think it's maybe
getting [inaudible] to get away

01:16:46.880 --> 01:16:48.730
from the language that
I consider tyrannical,

01:16:48.730 --> 01:16:51.050
and it's not my language.

01:16:51.050 --> 01:16:52.350
It's not Macedonian.

01:16:52.350 --> 01:16:55.380
This poor little language that
nobody likes to speak because,

01:16:55.380 --> 01:16:57.560
you know, only 2 million
people can read it,

01:16:57.560 --> 01:17:02.000
and I think [inaudible]
exists for such a short time.

01:17:02.000 --> 01:17:03.860
For me, English is tyrannical.

01:17:03.860 --> 01:17:06.760
People are expecting us to
be translated into English

01:17:06.760 --> 01:17:10.140
and to become someone
somewhere int his world,

01:17:10.140 --> 01:17:11.920
which is such a dream.

01:17:11.920 --> 01:17:16.240
Like, I mean, dream in like
the American dream, you know.

01:17:16.240 --> 01:17:17.890
It's not going to happen.

01:17:17.890 --> 01:17:20.520
So, but it always
puts us in this --

01:17:20.520 --> 01:17:23.970
it gives us so much pressure
instead of just, you know,

01:17:23.970 --> 01:17:25.980
doing what you're
comfortable with.

01:17:25.980 --> 01:17:27.870
So, I believe it has to be --

01:17:27.870 --> 01:17:33.050
it has to be individual
for each person.

01:17:33.050 --> 01:17:37.390
&gt;&gt; Kateryna Babkina: In addition
to what both [inaudible]

01:17:37.390 --> 01:17:43.380
and Alisa said, which I share
